1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 d6 $6 4. d5 ({Also good for White are} 4. Bb5 {, which is the Steinitz Variation in the Ruy Lopez}) ({, and} 4. Nc3) 4... Nce7 (4... Nb8 5. c4 $16 {[%cal Gb1c3] leads to a King's Indian Petrosian Variation with two extra tempi for White.}) 5. c4 g6 (5... f5 {is premature due to} 6. exf5 $1 ({Also good is} 6. Nc3) 6... Nxf5 7. Nc3 Nf6 8. h3 $1 {[%cal Gg2g4] Threatening g2-g4, to push the knight back to e7 and win useful space on the kingside.} (8. Bd3 {, followed by Qc2, is also good enough for an advantage.}) 8... e4 (8... g6 9. g4 $1 Ne7 10. Bg2 Bg7 11. Ng5 O-O 12. Be3 $18) 9. Ng5 Qe7 10. Be2 (10. Qe2 {can be answered with} Nd4 {, and White has nothing better than} 11. Qd2 Nf5) 10... g6 (10... h6 $2 {does not work due to} 11. Bh5+ $1) 11. g4 Nh4 12. Qc2 $16 {[%csl Re4]} e3 $6 13. O-O $1 $18 ({But not} 13. Bxe3 $2 Ng2+ $13)) 6. Nc3 Bg7 (6... f5 7. exf5 (7. c5 $5 Nf6 8. Bb5+ Kf7 9. O-O $16 {is also very good for White.}) 7... gxf5 8. Ng5 Nf6 9. Be2 {Now Bh5+ can hardly be prevented, as h7-h5 would leave White full control over the g5-square and a stable knight there.} Bg7 10. Bh5+ Ng6 11. Nxh7 Nxh7 (11... Nxh5 $2 12. Qxh5 Kf7 13. Ng5+ Kf6 14. Qe2 $18) 12. Bxg6+ Kf8 13. h4 Qf6 14. Bh5 $16) 7. c5 $1 dxc5 (7... Nf6 8. cxd6 cxd6 9. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2c4]} O-O 10. Be2 Ne8 11. Nc4 f5 12. f3 $16 {[%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5] is a very good King's Indian for White, who will play a2-a4-a5 next.}) 8. Qb3 Nf6 {Black needs to take care of his development.} (8... b6 {is even worse:} 9. Bc4 {[%cal Gd5d6]} f6 10. h4 Bh6 11. O-O Bxc1 12. Raxc1 a6 13. a4 Nh6 14. Nd2 Nf7 ({Or} 14... Kf8 15. f4) 15. f4 Qd6 16. Ne2 $16) 9. Be3 O-O (9... b6 10. Nxe5 O-O 11. O-O-O $16) 10. Bxc5 b6 11. Ba3 $16 *

