1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 d5 (4... Be7 $6 5. Nc3 (5. Nxc6 $5 bxc6 6. Bd3 {is also good, as it basically leads to an improved version of the regular Scotch positions.}) 5... Nf6 6. Nxc6 dxc6 (6... bxc6 $2 7. e5 $18) 7. Qxd8+ Bxd8 8. Bf4 Be6 9. O-O-O $16 {[%cal Gf2f3] This is like a Berlin endgame in which White still has the pair of bishops. Black has no compensation for his inferior pawn structure and is tied to the defence of c7 for the moment.}) (4... Nge7 $6 5. Nc3 Nxd4 ({Black would like to play} 5... g6 $2 {, but this loses immediately to} 6. Bg5 $1 Bg7 7. Nd5 $18) 6. Qxd4 Nc6 7. Qe3 Nb4 (7... Bb4 8. Bd2 O-O (8... d6 9. a3 Bc5 10. Qg3 O-O 11. O-O-O $16) 9. a3 Ba5 10. O-O-O d6 11. f4 $16) 8. Qe2 {[%cal Ga2a3]} Bc5 9. a3 Nc6 10. Be3 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1] White will castle long and start attacking on the kingside.}) (4... d6 $6 {Played with the idea to prevent the standard Nxc6 and e4-e5.} 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. Nxc6 $5 (6. Bb5 Bd7 7. O-O {again leads to the Steinitz Variation.}) 6... bxc6 7. Bd3 Be7 (7... g6 {would be desirable, but White has} 8. e5 $1 dxe5 9. Qf3 Bd7 (9... Nd5 $2 {1/2-1/2 (49) Gavrilescu,D (2518)-Anand,V (2751) Warsaw 2022} 10. Nxd5 cxd5 (10... Qxd5 $2 11. Be4) 11. Bb5+ Bd7 12. Qxd5 Bxb5 13. Qxb5+ Qd7 14. Qxe5+ Qe7 15. Qxe7+ Bxe7 16. Be3 $18) 10. Bg5 Be7 11. O-O-O O-O 12. Bc4 {White has more than enough initiative for the pawn, for example} Ne8 13. Be3 $1 Nd6 14. Bb3 Bg5 (14... a5 15. Ba4 $1 Ra6 16. Rhe1 $16) 15. Rhe1 Bxe3+ 16. Qxe3 Re8 17. h3 $14 {[%csl Rc6,Re5]}) 8. O-O O-O 9. f4 Re8 10. Qf3 Bf8 11. Kh1 $16 {White will play Bd2, Re1, and eventually start attacking on the kingside.}) (4... Nxd4 5. Qxd4 Qf6 6. Qc4 $5 {Now the attack against the c7-pawn is unpleasant to deal with for Black.} (6. e5 Qb6 {gives Black good chances to equalise.}) 6... Bd6 (6... c6 7. Nc3 Bd6 (7... b5 8. Qd3 $16) 8. g3 $16 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) 7. Nc3 Ne7 8. Nb5 Nc6 9. Nxd6+ Qxd6 10. Bd2 Qe6 11. Bc3 $14) 5. exd5 (5. Bb5 {is also good:} dxe4 6. Nc3 ({Not so clear is} 6. Nxc6 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 a6 8. Ba4 Bd7) 6... Bd7 7. O-O Nf6 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Qe2 Be7 11. Rd1 Qb8 12. Nxe4 O-O $14) ({Another good alternative is} 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. exd5 Nf6 $5 (6... cxd5 $2 7. Bb5+) (6... Qxd5 7. Qe2+ Qe6 8. Nc3 $14) 7. dxc6 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Ng4 9. Be3 $1 Nxe3+ 10. fxe3 Rb8 11. b3 h5 $1 12. Nc3 Rh6 13. Kd2 $14 {Black will play a7-a6 and take on c6, after which White only has a small advantage in the endgame, as the bishop pair provides reasonable compensation for the sacrificed pawn.}) 5... Qxd5 6. Qe2+ Be6 (6... Nge7 $2 7. Nb5 $18) 7. Nxe6 fxe6 8. Nc3 Bb4 9. Bd2 Qf5 10. Qb5 O-O-O 11. Bd3 Qe5+ (11... Qf7 12. Be3 Nf6 13. O-O $14) 12. Qxe5 Nxe5 13. Be2 Nf6 14. O-O-O Neg4 15. Rdf1 $14 {The endgame with the pair of bishops and the superior pawn structure is very promising for White.} *

