1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 g6 $6 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Be3 {Preparing Qd2, f3, 0-0-0, followed by an eventual h2-h4-h5.} Nf6 (6... d6 7. Qd2 Nf6 8. f3 O-O 9. O-O-O $16 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gh2h4]}) (6... Nge7 $6 7. Qd2 d5 (7... d6 $6 8. O-O-O O-O 9. h4 h5 10. f3 $18 {[%cal Gg2g4]}) 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. O-O-O $16) 7. Nxc6 $1 (7. Qd2 {is too timid here:} O-O 8. O-O-O Re8 9. f3 d5 {Now Black gets the counterplay he wants in this variation.} 10. Bb5 Bd7 $11) 7... bxc6 ({No better is} 7... dxc6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. O-O-O+ Ke8 10. f3 $16 {, with a clearly better endgame for White.}) 8. e5 Ng8 (8... Nd5 $6 {looks like an active attempt, but after the simple} 9. Nxd5 cxd5 10. Qxd5 Rb8 11. O-O-O $18 {there is just no way for Black to generate serious counterplay.}) 9. f4 Nh6 (9... d6 10. Qf3 Ne7 11. Bc4 O-O 12. O-O-O $16) (9... f6 $2 10. Bc4 fxe5 11. O-O $18) (9... Ne7 10. Qf3 $16) 10. Qf3 O-O 11. O-O-O d5 {Threatening Bg4.} 12. h3 f6 13. Bc5 $16 {Now Black is forced to give up the exchange for insufficient compensation with Be6 or fxe5, as the alternatives lose immediately:} Re8 $2 (13... Rf7 $2 14. Bb5 $1 $18 Bb7 15. e6) 14. Nxd5 $1 cxd5 15. Rxd5 Bd7 16. Bc4 Kh8 17. e6 $18 *

