1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Qh4 {Years ago this move has been fairly popular, but in the computer age, ways to a white advantage have been found.} 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. Be2 $1 Qxe4 {The only consistent move.} (6... Nge7 $6 7. O-O O-O 8. Ndb5 $1 Ba5 9. Nd5 $16 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gb5c7]}) (6... d6 $6 7. O-O $16) (6... Bxc3+ $6 7. bxc3 Qxe4 8. O-O Nge7 9. Re1 O-O 10. Nb5 $16 {[%csl Rc7]}) (6... Nf6 $6 7. O-O Nxe4 $2 8. Nd5 Bc5 9. g3 Qd8 10. Nb5 Bb6 11. Bd3 $18) 7. Ndb5 $1 Bxc3+ ({The immediate} 7... Kd8 $6 {is worse because after} 8. O-O Bxc3 {, White can take back with the knight.} 9. Nxc3 Qd4 10. Bd2 $16 {[%csl Rd8]}) 8. bxc3 Kd8 9. O-O Nf6 ({No better is} 9... a6 $6 10. Nd4 Nxd4 11. cxd4 Nf6 12. Bf3 Qf5 13. c4 $16) 10. Bg5 $5 ({The main move in this position is} 10. Re1 {, followed by} Qd5 11. Nd4 {White should have more than enough compensation for the pawn, but Black's position is solid, and not easy to break open.}) 10... Qe5 ({After} 10... d6 {, White can quickly obtain a dominating position, for example} 11. Re1 Bd7 12. Bxf6+ gxf6 13. Bf3 Qg6 14. Rb1 Rc8 15. Nd4 Nxd4 16. cxd4 b6 17. Bh5 Qg7 18. Rb3 $16) 11. Qd2 d6 12. Rad1 Re8 13. Rfe1 {With simple positional play, White can increase the pressure and exploit the long-term problems Black has due to his uncastled king.} Be6 (13... Qc5 14. Nd4 $16) 14. c4 $16 Kc8 15. Bf4 Qc5 {Unsurprisingly, the concentrated activity of White's forces offers a tactical solution:} 16. Nxc7 Ne4 17. Bf1 $3 Nxd2 18. Nxe8 Kd7 19. Nxd6 Ke7 20. Rxd2 {[%csl Re7]} Qb4 21. c3 $1 Qxc3 22. Ne4 Qa5 23. Bd6+ Ke8 24. Ree2 $1 Rd8 25. Rd5 $1 Qb6 26. Bc5 Qb1 27. Nd6+ Rxd6 28. Bxd6 Kd7 29. Rb2 (29. Rdd2 $144 $16) 29... Qxb2 30. Be5+ Bxd5 31. Bxb2 Be6 32. Bxg7 Na5 33. Bd3 h5 34. Be2 Bxc4 35. Bxh5 Bxa2 36. Bc3 b6 (36... Nc6 37. Be2 {leads to a similar position.}) 37. h4 {[%csl Gh4]} Ke7 38. Bf3 $16 *

