1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bb4+ 5. c3 Bc5 {This may look like a loss of tempo, but now White cannot develop his queen's knight to its most natural square c3 anymore.} 6. Be3 Bb6 (6... Qf6 {doesn't make much sense here, as there is no serious pressure on d4 and Black is just a tempo down to another theoretical line from 4...Qf6.} 7. g3 $5 ({Also good is} 7. Be2 Nge7 8. Qd2) 7... Nge7 8. Bg2 d6 9. O-O O-O 10. Nc2 ({Or} 10. Qd2 $144 $5) 10... Kh8 11. Nd2 Bxe3 12. Nxe3 $16 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) {Now Black stands ready to play d7-d5 or Nge7 and d7-d5, but White strikes first:} 7. Nf5 $1 {Forcing a concession on the kingside.} g6 (7... Qf6 $6 {keeps the kingside pawns intact but neglects protection of the queenside, which White can exploit while developing:} 8. Na3 $1 {[%cal Ga3b5]} Nge7 9. Nb5 Kd8 10. Qd2 $16 {The uncastled king will be a permanent problem for Black.}) (7... Bxe3 8. Nxe3 Nf6 ({Or} 8... d6 9. c4 {[%cal Gb1c3]}) 9. f3 O-O 10. c4 {[%cal Gb1c3]} d6 11. Nc3 $14 {[%cal Gf1e2,Gd1d2,Ge1g1] Black is in a very passive position, lacking space and any reasonable pawn breaks.}) (7... d5 $5 {may be Black's best chance.} 8. Nxg7+ {The critical move.} ({Less convincing is} 8. Qxd5 Bxf5 9. Qxd8+ Rxd8 10. exf5 Nf6 $44 {After 0-0 and Re8, Black has an active position and good compensation for the pawn.}) 8... Kf8 9. Nh5 Qh4 $146 (9... Bxe3 $6 {was played in a few games, but after} 10. fxe3 Qg5 11. Nf4 dxe4 12. Be2 Nf6 13. O-O $16 {, White's position is clearly preferable. The knight on f4 is very strong and Black's king will always be vulnerable.}) 10. Ng3 dxe4 (10... Bxe3 $6 11. fxe3 Nf6 12. exd5 Bg4 13. Be2 $16) 11. Qd2 Qe7 {Now Black has some active ideas like Bg4 and Rad8 or h7-h5, which White should forestall with} 12. Bh6+ Nxh6 13. Qxh6+ Ke8 14. Be2 e3 (14... Ne5 $2 {is bad due to} 15. Nd2 {, and if Black defends his central pawn with} f5 {, the king is too open in the centre.} 16. Nc4 $18) 15. f4 $14 {[%cal Gb1a3] White is better due to his safer king and healthy structure, but Black's bishop pair provides some compensation.}) 8. Bxb6 axb6 9. Ne3 Nf6 (9... Qe7 10. Bd3 Nf6 11. O-O O-O 12. c4 $16 {[%cal Gb1c3]}) (9... d6 10. c4 $16 {[%cal Gb1c3]}) 10. f3 O-O {Attempts to prevent White from playing c3-c4 fall short:} (10... d5 $6 11. exd5 Qe7 12. Kf2 Ne5 13. Be2 O-O 14. Qd4 $16) (10... Qe7 {requires some precision from White:} 11. Be2 $1 O-O (11... Qc5 12. Qd2) 12. c4 Qc5 13. Qd2 Nd4 {Threatening Nb3.} (13... Nb4 14. Nc3 Qxe3 15. Qxe3 Nc2+ 16. Kd2 Nxe3 17. Kxe3 d6 18. g4 $16 {White has a large space advantage and c7 is very vulnerable.}) 14. Bd1 $1 b5 15. b4 Qe5 16. Nc3 c5 17. Rb1 $1 d6 18. O-O Bd7 19. Re1 $14 {1-0 (43) Natera,L (2143)-Hrzina,B (2059) ICCF email 2016 Now that White has fended off all the threats, Black's weaknesses on the queenside will soon become relevant.}) (10... Nh5 11. g3 $14) 11. c4 $1 {[%cal Gb1c3]} d5 $5 {The only chance to create counterplay. If Black tries to play with equal material, he is just doomed to passivity in a very cramped position.} (11... d6 12. Nc3 Nh5 13. Qd2 $16) (11... Nh5 12. Qd2 Na5 13. Na3 $1 $16) 12. cxd5 ({Less clear is} 12. Nxd5 $6 Ne5 $44 {[%cal Gc7c6]}) 12... Nxe4 13. fxe4 Qh4+ 14. Kd2 $1 ({Also possible is} 14. Ke2 Qxe4 15. Nd2 Qf4 {, but Black's counterplay looks more dangerous here than in the mainline.}) 14... Qxe4 15. Bd3 Qd4 (15... Qb4+ $2 16. Nc3 Ne5 17. Qb3 Qd4 18. Ne2 $18) 16. Qb3 $1 Re8 17. Re1 Ne5 18. Na3 $1 (18. Qc3 {is worse due to} Qf4 $13 {, and the pin against White's knight is unpleasant to deal with.}) 18... Bd7 19. Nac2 Qf4 20. Qc3 (20. a4 $5 {is also good.}) 20... Ra5 (20... c5 21. Be2 Rac8 {1-0 (54) Christiansen,J (2582) -Theodorou,N (2577) Warsaw 2021 After} 22. Rad1 b5 23. Kc1 $18 {, White had consolidated his extra piece and retained a decisive advantage.}) 21. Qd4 $1 Qxh2 22. Be2 Ra4 23. Qc3 Qg3 24. a3 f5 25. b4 $16 {Black still has some counterplay against White's vulnerable king, but the extra piece should prove its worth in the long run.} *

