1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Qf6 $5 {Putting pressure on the centralised knight immediately. Basically, Black wants to play the 4...Bc5 line without giving White the option of 5.Nb3, which I recommend in this repertoire.} 5. Nf3 $5 {Blocking the queen's pressure against f2 and preparing to attack her majesty with Nc3-d5 or Bg5 later.} (5. c3 Bc5 {This is Black's idea, White can no longer play Nb3. After} 6. Be3 Nge7 {, a well-known theoretical position from the 4...Bc5 line is reached.}) (5. Nxc6 Bc5 {is a well-known tabiya that can also arise after 4...Bc5 5.Nxc6 Qf6 but is not part of this repertoire.}) ({The immediate} 5. Nb3 {is met by} Qg6 {, hitting e4 and g2. Black has a satisfactory position here.}) 5... Bb4+ {Provoking c2-c3 first.} (5... Bc5 {is also playable, but now White's queen's knight can become very active.} 6. Nc3 Nge7 {Now White has two options:} 7. Bg5 $1 (7. Nb5 $5 Bb6 8. Be3 O-O $5 $146 (8... Ba5+ 9. c3 O-O 10. Bc4 $14) (8... Bxe3 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 Bh6 11. c3 Qf4 $1 (11... b6 12. Qa4 Bb7 13. Nxb6 axb6 14. Ba6 Ba8 15. Rd1 $14 {With rook and two pawns for the two pieces and the favourable structure and king's position.}) 12. Be2 Qb8 13. Qb3 Rf8 14. O-O Qxa8 $13 {The position is very chaotic and complicated, with chances for both sides.}) 9. Bxb6 axb6 10. Nxc7 ({After} 10. c3 d5 11. Nxc7 Ra5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 Bh3 $1 $132 {[%cal Gf8e8] , Black has dangerous counterplay.}) 10... Ra5 11. Be2 Qxb2 12. O-O Rxa2 (12... d6 $5 {is also possible.}) 13. Rxa2 Qxa2 14. Nb5 (14. Nd5 Qa5) 14... d5 15. Nc3 Qa5 16. Nxd5 Bg4 $11 {Black is very close to equality here. He plans to take on f3 and d5, to play with an active knight against a restricted bishop.}) 7... Qg6 (7... Qe6 {Now the queen can protect c7 from d7 after d7-d6 is played, but generally this placement is less active than g6.} 8. Bd3 d6 9. Qe2 h6 (9... O-O 10. O-O-O {is similar.}) 10. Be3 Bxe3 11. Qxe3 a6 12. O-O-O O-O 13. Rhe1 $14 {White has the better structure and active prospects on the kingside. His next moves can be Kb1, Nd4 and f2-f4.}) 8. Bd3 {seems best, and now Black should play} (8. Qd2 d6 9. O-O-O Bg4 $11 {looks satisfactory for Black.}) (8. Qe2 h6 9. Be3 Bb4 10. Bd2 d6 11. a3 Ba5 {, and now an interesting line is} 12. Nd5 ({After} 12. O-O-O Be6 13. Nd5 Bxd2+ 14. Rxd2 {, Black can castle queenside and reach a satisfactory position.} O-O-O $11) 12... Bxd2+ 13. Nxd2 Nxd5 14. exd5+ Kd8 15. O-O-O Re8 16. Qc4 Ne5 17. Qc3 Nd7 18. Bd3 Qf6 $11 {White cannot easily avoid a queen swap because Black will then follow up with Nc5 and possibly Bf5, with an active position.}) 8... Ne5 (8... d6 $2 9. Nd5 $18 {is one of the points of the previous move.}) (8... h6 $6 9. e5 Qe6 10. Bxe7 Nxe7 11. O-O $16 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf1e1,Gc3b5]}) (8... O-O 9. O-O $36 {White threatens to play e5 or Nd5 next and overall has a very harmonious development.}) 9. Qd2 $1 $146 (9. h4 {can be safely answered with} d6) 9... Nxd3+ {The critical move.} (9... f6 $6 10. Nxe5 Qxg5 11. f4 Qh6 12. Nf3 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1] is very pleasant for White, who will castle long and start play on the kingside.}) (9... Nxf3+ $6 {only improves White's position, who will castle long and make use of the g-file.} 10. gxf3 $16) 10. Qxd3 f6 (10... h6 $6 {seems worse:} 11. Be3 Qxg2 12. Rg1 Qxf3 13. Bxc5 Qxd3 14. cxd3 d6 15. Bd4 {Black has to give back the pawn while staying under pressure.} Be6 16. Bxg7 Rh7 17. Bf6 $16 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gf2f4]}) 11. Nb5 $1 (11. Be3 Qxg2 $13 {is clearly an improvement on the 10...h6 line for Black.}) 11... Bb6 (11... fxg5 $6 12. Nxc7+ Kd8 13. Nxa8 Nc6 14. O-O-O $16 {is clearly better for White. Even though the knight is trapped, Black has no easy way of winning it.}) 12. Be3 $1 Ba5+ 13. Bd2 Bb6 (13... Bxd2+ 14. Nxd2 $16 {[%csl Rc7]}) 14. O-O-O a6 {, and now White has to play the strong move} 15. Qa3 $1 {keeping his knight on b5 active and Black's king in the centre.} Qxg2 (15... d6 16. Be3 $1 Bxe3+ 17. fxe3 axb5 18. Qxa8 Qxg2 19. Nd2 $16 {Black does not have sufficient compensation for the exchange.}) 16. Nbd4 {[%cal Gh1g1]} Qg6 (16... Bxd4 {is met with the intermediate move} 17. Rhg1 $1 Qxf2 18. Rdf1 $16 {, and now for example} Bxb2+ 19. Qxb2 Qe2 20. e5 {provides White with a huge initiative.}) 17. Rhg1 Qf7 18. Nf5 $1 Nxf5 19. exf5 d6 20. Rge1+ $1 Kf8 (20... Kd8 $2 21. Ng5 $1 Qh5 22. Ne4 $1 Bxf5 23. Nxd6 $18) 21. Bh6 $1 Bxf5 (21... gxh6 22. Rxd6 $18 {is just crushing.}) 22. Rxd6 $1 cxd6 23. Qxd6+ Kg8 24. Re7 Rd8 25. Qb4 Bxf2 (25... gxh6 26. Rxf7 Kxf7 27. Qxb6 Rd7 28. Nd4 Re8 29. b3 $16) 26. Qxb7 Bg6 27. Rxf7 Bxf7 28. Bd2 $16 {[%cal Ga2a4] White will soon be ready to push his queenside pawns while Black has to spend two moves for his king's rook to enter play.}) 6. c3 Bc5 7. Be2 {Now Black has different options:} h6 {Preventing any Bg5-ideas.} (7... Nge7 8. O-O h6 {transposes to 7...h6.} (8... Ng6 $6 9. b4 $1 Bb6 10. Nbd2 Nf4 11. Nc4 $16 {a2-a4-a5 is an unpleasant positional threat.}) (8... d6 {transposes to 7...d6.})) (7... d6 8. O-O a6 $5 $146 (8... Nge7 9. b4 $1 Bb6 10. Nbd2 $1 $146 ({Previously,} 10. Bg5 {has been played, but after} Qg6 11. Bh4 a5 12. b5 Ne5 $13 {, the position is just very complicated, with chances for both sides.}) 10... O-O (10... Qxc3 11. Rb1 Qf6 12. Nc4 $36 {[%cal Gc1b2] White has more than enough compensation for the pawn.}) (10... Be6 11. b5 $1 Na5 (11... Ne5 12. Nd4 N7g6 13. N2b3 $14 {White stands ready to play f2-f4. If Black prevents this with} Nf4 14. Bxf4 Qxf4 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Nd4 {gives White good play, as he can increase the pressure against e6 with Qb3.}) 12. Nd4 O-O 13. Nxe6 fxe6 (13... Qxe6 14. c4 $14) 14. Nf3 Ng6 15. g3 $1 {Restricting Black's knight on g6.} h6 16. Kg2 $14 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] Eventually, White will continue h2-h4-h5.}) 11. a4 a5 ({After} 11... a6 12. Nc4 Ba7 13. Bg5 $36 {[%cal Gb4b5] , White is very active.}) 12. Nc4 $1 (12. b5 Ne5 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. Nc4 Bc5 $11 {is satisfactory for Black.}) 12... axb4 13. Bg5 Qe6 14. Nxb6 cxb6 15. cxb4 Nxb4 16. Re1 Nec6 17. Bb5 $14 {[%csl Gb5,Rb6,Rd6,Gg5] The pair of bishops and Black's structural weaknesses give White more than enough compensation for the pawn.}) (8... a5 $146 {Surprisingly, this move hasn't been played before, but it makes a lot of sense to prevent b2-b4.} 9. Nbd2 Qg6 (9... Nge7 10. e5 $1 Nxe5 ({The point is that} 10... dxe5 {loses material to} 11. Ne4) 11. Ne4 Qf5 12. Nxc5 dxc5 13. Re1 O-O 14. Nxe5 Qxe5 15. Bf3 Qf6 16. Be3 $14 {Black can hardly hold on to his extra pawn while the two bishops will remain very strong.}) 10. Nb3 $5 Bb6 11. Re1 Nge7 12. Nbd4 O-O 13. Be3 $14 {White can continue with Qd2 and possibly Nb5, exploiting the weaknesses created by a7-a5.}) (8... h6 $6 {does not work so well here due to} 9. b4 $1 Bb6 (9... Bxb4 $2 10. cxb4 Qxa1 11. Qc2 Qf6 (11... Nxb4 {leads to a long and forced line after which White is clearly better:} 12. Qb3 Qxa2 13. Bb5+ $1 c6 14. Qxb4 cxb5 15. Nc3 Qc4 16. Qxd6 Qe6 17. Qg3 Ne7 18. Nxb5 $16 {[%cal Gb5c7]}) (11... Nd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Bb2 Qxb4 14. Bxg7 Rh7 15. Bc3 Qc5 16. Nd2 $16 {White is far ahead in development and has too many threats.}) 12. Bb2 Ne5 13. Nd4 Qe7 (13... Qd8 14. Nb5 c6 {loses immediately:} 15. Rd1 $1 cxb5 16. Bxe5 $18) 14. f4 Ng6 (14... Ng4 15. Qc1 $16) 15. Nf5 Bxf5 16. exf5 Qe3+ 17. Kh1 Nxf4 18. Nc3 Nf6 (18... Nxe2 19. Nd5 $1 $18) 19. Bc1 Qe7 20. Bxf4 $16 {In this materially imbalanced position, the two minor pieces are clearly stronger than Black's extra rook.}) 10. Nbd2 Nge7 (10... Qxc3 $2 {is too greedy, and after} 11. Rb1 Qf6 12. a4 a6 13. Bb2 $18 {, the pressure against Black's undeveloped position becomes too strong.}) 11. a4 a6 (11... a5 12. b5 Ne5 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. Nc4 Bc5 15. Be3 $1 Bxe3 16. fxe3 $1 {Not giving Black any respite.} Qg5 17. h4 $1 Qxh4 18. Nxe5 O-O 19. Bc4 Be6 20. Bxe6 fxe6 21. Qd7 $16) 12. Nc4 Ba7 13. Kh1 $1 {[%cal Gb4b5] A strong prophylactic move. Now after} Ng6 14. b5 {, Black has no 14...axb5 15.axb5 Bxf2+ anymore.} Nce7 15. b6 Bxb6 16. Nxb6 cxb6 17. Ba3 O-O 18. Qxd6 Qxd6 19. Bxd6 $16 {White has the clearly better ending due to the pair of bishops and the weakness on b6.}) 9. b4 Ba7 10. Kh1 $5 Nge7 ({After} 10... h6 {, White plays} 11. Bb2 {followed by Qc2 or Qb3 and Nd2-c4.}) 11. Bg5 Qg6 12. Nbd2 f6 13. Bh4 O-O 14. a4 Kh8 15. b5 Ne5 16. Bg3 Nxf3 17. Bxf3 Rb8 18. Re1 $14 {White is slightly better due to his space advantage and his somewhat more active pieces.}) 8. O-O Nge7 9. Qc2 $5 (9. c4 d6 10. Nc3 Bg4 $11 {is satisfactory for Black, who has good dark-square control.}) ({Now} 9. b4 Bxb4 10. cxb4 Qxa1 11. Na3 ({or} 11. Qb3 Nd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Bb2 Qb6 $132) 11... Qf6 12. Nb5 Kd8 $132 {is not at all clear. White has obvious compensation for the sacrificed material but no clear advantage or even a winning attack, like in the lines analysed above.}) (9. Qd2 {has also been played, but after} d6 10. b4 Bb6 11. c4 ({or} 11. Bb2 Qg6) 11... Bg4 12. Bb2 Qg6 13. Kh1 O-O 14. b5 Nd8 $13 {[%cal Gd8e6] , the position is very unclear.}) 9... O-O $146 (9... a5 $6 {weakens some important squares on the queenside, which can be exploited immediately with} 10. Na3 $1 {[%cal Ga3b5] , and Black has to part with one of his bishops.} Bxa3 ({After} 10... O-O 11. Nb5 Bb6 12. Be3 $36 {[%csl Rc7] , White has a lot of pressure.}) 11. bxa3 O-O 12. Bb2 Ng6 13. c4 $36 {[%cal Gc4c5,Gc2c3] White will follow up with c4-c5 and Qc3.}) (9... d6 10. b4 Bb6 11. Bb2 O-O (11... Qg6 12. Nbd2) ({and} 11... Ne5 12. c4 {lead to similar positions.}) 12. c4 Qg6 13. b5 Nd8 14. a4 $14 {[%cal Gf3h4,Ga4a5,Ga1a3] It is important that} Bh3 $2 {does not work due to} 15. Nh4 Qg5 16. Ra3 $1 $18) (9... a6 10. b4 Ba7 11. Bb2 O-O ({Now after} 11... Qg6 12. Nbd2 d6 13. Rae1 $1 O-O 14. a3 $1 {Preparing c3-c4} f5 (14... Bh3 15. Nh4 Qf6 16. Ndf3) 15. Bc4+ Kh8 16. Bd3 $36 {, all of White's pieces are very well positioned and his king is safer.}) 12. c4 $5 ({Now} 12. a3 {is somewhat slow and Black can equalise with} d5) 12... Nxb4 13. Qd2 Qd6 14. Qc3 f6 15. Qb3 Bc5 16. Nc3 Qe6 17. a3 Nbc6 18. Nd5 $14 {Winning back the pawn on c7, with the better position.}) (9... Ng6 10. b4 Bb6 11. Na3 d6 12. Nc4 $36 {, and Black has to deal with the unpleasant threat a2-a4-a5.}) 10. b4 (10. Nbd2 a5 $11 {, and White doesn't have the desired Na3-b5 manoeuvre.}) 10... Bb6 11. a4 (11. Nbd2 $5 {followed by Bb2 also looks good.}) 11... a6 12. Nbd2 d6 13. Bb2 $14 {[%cal Ga4a5,Gc3c4] Black's position is very solid, but White's space advantage should not be without use, for example} Ng6 14. a5 Ba7 15. c4 Nd4 16. Nxd4 Bxd4 17. Bxd4 Qxd4 18. Rfe1 $14 {[%cal Ge2f1,Ga1d1] White's plan could be to further consolidate his position with Bf1 and Ra3-e3 and then play Nb1-c3-d5 at an appropriate moment.} *

