45,47,19,19,19]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 (5. Nxc6 Qf6
{is a well-known tabiya, that can also arise after 4...Qf6 5.Nxc6 Bc5, but is
not part of this repertoire.}) (5. Be3 Qf6 6. c3 {has been one of the
theoretical mainlines for many years.}) 5... Bb4+ {The two moves seen in this
chapter are generally solid and less theoretical than the mainline 5...Bb6,
but also rather passive. As often in the Scotch, the purpose of this check is
to provoke c2-c3 and thus prevent the most active queen's knight development
to c3. On the other hand, the pawn can be quite useful on c3, controlling an
important central square.} (5... Be7 {has also been played:} 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. Bc4
$5 {An unusual square for the bishop when a knight is placed on b3. One idea
of this move is to provoke Ne5 and later play f2-f4 with gain of tempo.} ({
Also good are} 7. g3) ({and} 7. f4) 7... O-O 8. O-O d6 ({After} 8... Bb4 $6 {
, White can simply sacrifice the central pawn with} 9. Nd5 {and gain a huge
initiative:} Nxe4 10. Qf3 Nf6 11. Bg5 Be7 12. Nxe7+ Qxe7 13. Rfe1 Qd8 14. Bb5
$36) 9. Re1 Re8 ({The pawn structure after} 9... Be6 10. Bxe6 fxe6 {is
generally preferable for White.}) 10. Bf4 (10. h3 {also looks good.}) 10... Bf8
11. h3 Be6 {Now that Black is ready to take back with the rook, White simply
withdraws the bishop.} 12. Bf1 $14 {White has a pleasant space advantage and
his pieces are harmonious. If Black tries to relocate his Nc6, White always
has the reply Nd4.}) 6. c3 Be7 7. f4 $1 d6 (7... a5 8. a4 {is always in
White's favour, who controls the b4-square with his b4-pawn, while at the same
time b5 has been seriously weakened.}) (7... Nf6 8. Bd3 {should transpose.}) 8.
N1d2 $1 ({Here} 8. Bd3 {is inferior due to the check} Bh4+ $5 9. g3 Be7 {
, and with the bishop already developed to d3, the light squares on the
kingside look rather weak.} 10. N1d2 Nf6 11. Nf3 O-O {[%csl Rg2,Rh3]}) 8... Nf6
({Now} 8... Bh4+ {is just a loss of tempo:} 9. g3 Be7 10. Bg2 Nf6 11. Nc4 O-O (
11... h5 {can be answered with} 12. h3) 12. O-O Re8 13. Ne3 Bf8 14. Qc2 Bd7 15.
Bd2 $16 {[%cal Ga1e1] White will play Rae1 before pushing his g-pawn while
Black is without any counterplay.}) 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O Re8 11. Qc2 Bf8 12. Nf3
a5 13. a4 g6 14. Bd2 $16 {[%cal Ga1e1] Again, Black's position is extremely
cramped and passive.} *

