1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 ({After} 5... dxc6 $6 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. f3 $14 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gc1e3,Ge3f4,Ge1c1] , Black has no compensation for his damaged pawn structure, as, unlike in the Berlin, White still has his bishop pair.}) 6. e5 Nd5 $6 (6... Ne4 $6 7. Nd2 $1 {Simple and good. White offers to trade Black's only active piece while developing his own pieces.} Nxd2 (7... Nc5 8. Nb3 {[%cal Gc1e3]} Qe7 9. f4 g6 10. Be3 Nxb3 11. axb3 {Black's pawn structure on the queenside causes long-term problems.} Bg7 (11... f6 {can be answered with the energetical} 12. Bd3 fxe5 13. O-O e4 14. f5 $1 exd3 15. Qxd3 $18 {, followed by Rae1.}) 12. Bd3 O-O 13. O-O d6 14. Ra5 $1 $16 {, with the idea} dxe5 $2 15. Bc5 $18) 8. Bxd2 Be7 9. Bd3 $16 {White has very harmonious development and the better structure.}) 7. c4 Nb6 ({After} 7... Ne7 {, with the idea to follow up with Ng6, White can play} 8. Bd3 Ng6 9. O-O Be7 10. Re1 ({Also possible but more complicated is} 10. f4 $5 d6 11. Qc2 $1 dxe5 12. Be4 O-O 13. f5 Qd4+ 14. Kh1 Nf4 15. Rd1 Qb6 16. Nc3 $36) 10... O-O 11. Nc3 d6 12. exd6 Bxd6 ({No better is} 12... cxd6 $6 13. Be3 Ne5 {1/2-1/2 (52) Belka,W (2436)-Anderson,B (2465) ICCF email 2012 , and now White should have played} 14. Bf1 Be6 15. b3 $16 {White has the better structure and will continue h2-h3, Qd2 and Rad1, possibly followed by f2-f4.}) 13. Ne4 Be5 ({Or} 13... Bb4 14. Bd2) 14. Rb1 $14 {Black's damaged pawn structure promises White a lasting advantage.}) (7... Bb4+ 8. Bd2 $1 ({Also good enough for a small advantage is} 8. Nd2 Nf4 9. a3 Be7 10. Nf3 Ne6 11. Bd3 $14) 8... Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 Nb6 (9... Ne7 $6 10. Nc3 O-O 11. O-O-O $16 {leaves Black seriously cramped, as there is no obvious way to solve the problem of his backward d-pawn.}) 10. Nc3 Qe7 (10... O-O 11. O-O-O {should transpose.}) 11. O-O-O O-O {Here White has several good moves that promise at least a slight advantage:} 12. Qf4 (12. f4 $5 $14) (12. Qd4 c5 13. Qe4 f5 14. Qf4 Re8 15. Qxf5 Rf8 16. Qh3 Qxe5 17. Bd3 $14) 12... Re8 13. Bd3 d6 (13... Qxe5 $6 14. Qh4 h6 15. Rhe1 $1 Qxe1 16. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 17. Kd2 Re8 18. c5 $1 Nd5 19. Nxd5 cxd5 20. g4 $1 $16 {[%cal Gg4g5] White has strong threats while Black's pieces are rather uncoordinated.}) 14. exd6 cxd6 15. Qe4 $5 {This forces a favourable endgame.} ({Also good is} 15. Be4 {, when Black should give up the pawn immediately:} d5 16. cxd5 Nxd5 17. Nxd5 cxd5 18. Bxd5 Bb7 19. Kb1 h6 $14 {Black's counterplay against the king and the drawish nature of many rook endgames offer him some chances to hold.}) 15... Qg5+ (15... g6 16. Qxe7 Rxe7 17. b3 $14 {[%csl Rc6,Rd6][%cal Gd3e4] , followed by Be4, is also clearly preferable for White.}) 16. f4 Rxe4 17. fxg5 Re5 18. Be4 ({Also good is} 18. Rhe1 Bg4 19. Rxe5 dxe5 20. Re1 $14 {, and again Black's weaknesses are the defining factor of the position.}) 18... Bf5 19. Bxc6 Rc8 20. Rxd6 ({Also good is} 20. Rhe1 Rxe1 21. Rxe1 Be6 22. c5 dxc5 23. Bf3 $14) 20... Nxc4 21. Rd4 Ne3 22. Bb7 Rb8 23. Bf3 Rc5 24. h4 $14 {Despite Black's counterplay, White has good chances to convert his extra pawn.}) 8. Be3 $5 ({Also possible is} 8. Bd3) ({and} 8. Nc3) 8... d5 (8... Bb4+ 9. Nd2 $1 {The point of White's last move. Now the queen can take back on d2.} Qe7 10. a3 Bc5 (10... Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 Qxe5 12. O-O-O {, followed by Bd4, gives White a strong initiative.}) 11. Bxc5 Qxc5 12. Nf3 O-O 13. Bd3 d5 14. cxd5 Nxd5 ({Or} 14... cxd5 15. O-O Qe7 16. h3 $16) 15. O-O Nf4 16. Rc1 Qa5 17. Re1 Ba6 18. Bxa6 Qxa6 19. Qc2 Ne6 {leaves White with an extra pawn and good winning chances after} ({Now} 19... Nd3 {can be met with} 20. Ng5 $1 h6 (20... g6 21. e6 $1) 21. Re3 Rad8 22. Rd1 $14) 20. h4 h6 21. Qxc6 Qxc6 22. Rxc6 Rfb8 23. Re2 $16) 9. exd6 cxd6 {This structure is generally favourable for White, who himself has no weaknesses.} ({The endgame after} 9... Bxd6 $6 10. c5 Be5 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. Nc3 Nd5 13. O-O-O $16 {is very unpleasant for Black, who has a hard time finding a safe square for his king.}) 10. Bd3 d5 ({Or} 10... Be7 11. Qc2 $14 {, followed by 0-0 and Nd2.}) 11. O-O $1 Be7 (11... dxc4 $6 {leads to a difficult endgame for Black after} 12. Be4 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Bb7 14. Nc3 Bb4 15. a4 $1 $16 {, threatening a4-a5-a6.}) (11... Be6 12. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gd1c2] , followed by Qc2, sees White finishing development first with a very pleasant position.}) (11... Nxc4 $6 12. Bd4 $1 {[%csl Re8] , and Black is seriously lacking in development and under pressure. Even the strong defence} Be6 13. b3 Qh4 14. f4 Nd6 15. Qc2 Rc8 16. Nd2 c5 17. Be5 c4 18. bxc4 dxc4 19. Be4 $16 {leaves him in an unenviable situation.}) 12. Nd2 O-O 13. c5 $5 ({Also good is the simple} 13. Qc2 {, followed by Rfe1 and Rad1.}) 13... d4 {The critical move and Black's only chance to reach a playable position.} ({After} 13... Nd7 14. Qc2 g6 15. Nf3 $16 {[%cal Ge3d4] , followed by Bd4, and b2-b4, White has achieved a perfect blockade of Black's central pawns.}) 14. Bf4 Nd5 ({After} 14... Bxc5 15. Qh5 f5 16. Nb3 Bd6 17. Qf3 Bxf4 18. Qxf4 Rf6 19. Rfd1 $16 {[%csl Rc6,Rd4] , Black cannot keep his extra pawn and will suffer due to his many long-term weaknesses.}) 15. Bg3 Nb4 (15... Bxc5 {can simply be answered with} 16. Qc2) 16. Bb1 $5 ({Black's idea is} 16. Bc4 d3 {when the advanced d-pawn provides him with some counterplay.}) 16... d3 ({After} 16... Ba6 17. Re1 {, Black has no good follow-up.}) 17. a3 {The idea of White's previous move.} Nc2 18. Bxc2 dxc2 19. Qxc2 Qd5 {Now if White clings to the c-pawn, Black can develop some activity after Bf5, so White should just rely on his positional advantage after} 20. Rfe1 $1 Qxc5 (20... Bxc5 $4 21. Re5 $18 {is one of the points of White's previous move.}) 21. Qxc5 Bxc5 22. Rac1 Bd4 23. Be5 Bxe5 24. Rxe5 $14 {[%csl Rc5] Black faces a long and difficult defence.} *

