1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. h4 g6 $5 (8... Nb6 $6 {This unprovoked withdrawal doesn't look very logical. Black wants to play a quick d7-d5, but this doesn't solve all of his problems.} 9. Nc3 {Simple and good - developing the knight to its most active square.} ({Also possible are} 9. h5) ({and} 9. Nd2) 9... d5 10. exd6 Qxe2+ 11. Nxe2 $5 ({Also good is} 11. Bxe2 cxd6 {0-1 (43) Lucas,A (2337)-Saravana,K (2340) Chess. com INT 2022 Now White should have played} 12. Be3 $16 {, with a stable advantage.}) 11... Bxd6 (11... cxd6 12. Nd4 Bd7 13. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Ge1c1] also gives White a long-term structural advantage.}) 12. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2c3,Ge1c1]} O-O ({Or} 12... Nc4 13. Bc3) 13. O-O-O Re8 14. Nc3 Bg4 15. f3 Be6 16. Ba6 $14 {[%csl Ra7,Rc6] Black faces a difficult defence due to his structural weaknesses.}) (8... Rb8 9. c4 Nb6 (9... Qb4+ $6 10. Kd1 $1 ({Also good is the simple} 10. Nd2 Nf4 11. Qe3 Ne6 12. Bd3 d5 13. exd6 Bxd6 14. O-O $14) 10... Ne7 (10... Nb6 11. b3 $16) (10... Ba6 11. b3 $16) 11. Rh3 $1 $16 {[%cal Gh3b3] While the king is surprisingly safe on d1, it becomes clear that Black's pseudo-active moves start to backfire and he has to lose more time finding a safe square for his queen.}) (9... Ba6 $6 10. b3 (10. Rh3 $5 {is also good, preparing Rh3-a3.}) 10... f6 11. Bb2 Nf4 (11... fxe5 12. g3 $16 {White can simply finish his development and profit from the fact that Black cannot castle long anymore.}) 12. Qe3 fxe5 13. Nd2 $16 {After White has consolidated his queenside, Black's bishop and rook on that side of the board don't make much sense anymore. And due to the attack against a7, Black cannot cling to his extra pawn.}) 10. Nc3 Qe6 11. h5 $5 {is an interesting alternative.} (11. b3 Bb4 ({After} 11... a5 12. Bb2 a4 13. O-O-O $16 {White's king is safe as Black's pieces on the queenside are not very effective.}) 12. Bb2 O-O 13. O-O-O f6 {Here White has two options: Or the immediate} 14. Ne4 $5 {[%cal Gc4c5]} (14. c5 $5 Bxc5 15. Ne4 Be7 16. exf6 gxf6 17. Rh3 (17. Qc2 d5 $13) 17... d5 18. Re3 dxe4 19. Rxe4 Qf5 20. Rxe7 Qc5+ 21. Kb1 Nd5 22. Re1 Bf5+ ({Now} 22... Nxe7 23. Qxe7 Qxe7 24. Rxe7 $44 {is very dangerous for Black.}) 23. Ka1 {And here Black can equalise with} Rxb3 24. Qc4 Qxc4 25. Bxc4 Rb4 $11) 14... fxe5 15. c5 Nd5 16. a3 {Trapping the bishop, so Black has to find some very precise moves.} Qh6+ 17. Kb1 Ba5 {Now going for the material is dangerous, so White should play} 18. Qc2 ({Or} 18. Qc4 d6 19. cxd6 Be6 $13) 18... d6 19. cxd6 Bf5 20. dxc7 Bxc7 21. Bc4 Kh8 $11 {, with the more pleasant position, also the computer considers it equal.})) (8... Qb4+ $6 9. Nd2 (9. c3 {is also good.}) 9... Nf4 10. Qe3 Nd5 {Of course there is no need to repeat moves. After} 11. Qg3 $16 {White has improved his queen and Black has achieved less than nothing.}) (8... h6 {Played to prevent any Bg5-ideas.} 9. Bd2 $5 $146 {is a new move that should create the most practical problems for Black.} (9. c4 Nb6 (9... Ba6 $6 10. Rh3 $1 {[%cal Gh3a3]}) (9... Qb4+ 10. Nd2 Nf4 11. Qe3 Ne6 12. Bd3 $14) 10. Nc3 Ba6 {Is very similar to the mainline. The insertion of h2-h4 and h7-g6 doesn't make much of a difference.} 11. Qe4 Qe6 12. b3 Bb4 13. Bd2 Bxc3 14. Bxc3 d5 15. Qf3 $5 dxc4 16. Be2 O-O 17. O-O Rad8 $11) {Against} 9... g6 ({After} 9... Nb4 10. Na3 Ba6 11. Qe4 d5 12. Qf4 $14 {, Black has played a few active moves, but there's not much of a result except for an unstable knight on b4 and a compromised pawn structure.}) (9... Rb8 $6 {Doesn't achieve anything after} 10. c4) (9... Qe6 10. Nc3 a5 11. O-O-O Nxc3 12. Bxc3 Bb4 {is very close to equality, but White keeps some pressure after} 13. Qc4 Qxc4 14. Bxc4 Bxc3 15. bxc3 Ba6 16. Bxa6 Rxa6 17. Rd4 Ke7 18. h5 a4 19. a3 Ra5 20. Rhd1 Rd8 21. f4 g6 $14) (9... d6 {gives White the usual endgame advantage after} 10. exd6 cxd6 11. Nc3 Qxe2+ 12. Bxe2 $14) {, White should play} 10. h5 g5 11. Nc3 Bg7 12. O-O-O O-O 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. f4 {Now Black has to find several difficult moves to reach equality:} d6 15. fxg5 Rb8 16. Bc3 $5 (16. gxh6 Bxe5 $13 {is the idea of Black's previous move.}) 16... Qxg5+ 17. Qd2 Qxd2+ 18. Rxd2 Be6 (18... dxe5 19. Rxd5 $14) 19. exd6 Bxc3 20. bxc3 cxd6 21. Rh4 Rfc8 22. Ra4 Rc7 $11) (8... Bb7 {Black prepares long castling immediately.} 9. c4 (9. Rh3 {doesn't achieve much after} Qe6 10. Rb3 Nb6 $13) 9... Nb6 10. Nc3 (10. Rh3 {can lead to a very complicated position after} O-O-O 11. a4 Ba6 12. a5 Bxc4 13. Qc2 Bxf1 14. axb6 Bb5 15. bxa7 Kb7 $13) 10... O-O-O (10... Qe6 11. Bd2 $1 {After other bishop moves, Bb4 can be unpleasant.} O-O-O (11... Bb4 12. O-O-O Ba6 (12... O-O 13. a3 $16) (12... O-O-O 13. Rh3 $1 Rhe8 14. Re3 $36) 13. b3 O-O 14. Qh5 $5 f5 15. Re1 $14 {[%cal Gf1d3] , followed by Bd3.}) 12. O-O-O Ba6 (12... Re8 {can be always met by} 13. Re1) 13. b3 Ba3+ 14. Kc2 $14 {Black has a cramped position due to White's strong pawn on e5.}) 11. Bf4 $1 (11. Bg5 {doesn't achieve very much:} f6 12. exf6 gxf6 13. Qxe7 Bxe7 14. Be3 d5 $11) (11. Bd2 Re8 $36) 11... d5 {This forces White to take the pawn:} (11... Ba6 12. b3 Qa3 $5 {Otherwise White will castle, with a good position.} (12... Re8 13. O-O-O $14) (12... f6 13. O-O-O $14) 13. Qc2 Bb4 14. Rc1 $1 {And now} d5 {leads to a complicated line, after which White keeps the upper hand:} 15. exd6 Rhe8+ 16. Be3 Rxd6 17. Be2 {If White manages to castle, his opponent's pieces on the queenside look comically bad, so Black has to force more complications:} Bxc4 18. bxc4 Na4 19. c5 Rd5 20. O-O Nxc3 21. Bf3 Rxe3 22. Bxd5 Ne2+ 23. Kh2 $16 {, and Black doesn't have sufficient compensation.}) (11... d6 $6 {is dubious as Black doesn't really want to take on e5.} 12. O-O-O dxe5 13. Qxe5 Rxd1+ 14. Nxd1 $16) 12. exd6 Qxe2+ 13. Bxe2 Bxd6 {Black is solid in this endgame, but White can play for a win without any risk.} 14. Bg5 $5 $146 {Provoking f7-f6.} (14. Be3 Be5) (14. Bxd6 cxd6 15. f3 Kc7 16. Kf2 Bc8 17. Rac1 Rhe8 18. Rhd1 a5 $11 {1/ 2-1/2 (54) Castignani,F (2095)-Van De Peut,A (1856) LSS email 2018}) 14... f6 (14... Rde8 15. O-O c5 16. Be3 $14 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gf1e1]}) 15. Bd2 {Taking the sting out of any Be5-ideas.} c5 (15... Rhe8 16. O-O-O) 16. O-O-O Be5 (16... Rhe8 17. b3) (16... Bxg2 $2 17. Rhg1 $16 {[%csl Rg7]}) 17. b3 Rhe8 18. Rde1 g6 19. f3 Bg3 20. Rd1 Be5 21. Bf1 $14 {[%cal Gc1c2,Gf1d3] White will play Kc2 and Bd3, slowly consolidating his advantage to exploit his better pawn structure in the long run.}) (8... h5 {prevents a further advance of White's h-pawn but also weakens Black's kingside. It's hard to imagine that the insertion of h2-h4 and h7-h5 is not favourable for White.} 9. c4 Ba6 (9... Nb6 10. Bg5 Qe6 11. Nd2 d6 12. exd6 Bxd6 (12... cxd6 13. Be3 $5 Be7 14. O-O-O $36 {It's hard to find a safe square on the board for Black's king.}) 13. O-O-O O-O $1 {This pawn sacrifice seems to be Black's best chance.} 14. Qxh5 (14. Nb3 $14 {is also good enough for a small advantage.}) 14... Na4 15. Bd3 g6 16. Qf3 Be5 {Now White has a choice: The simple} 17. b3 {seems best:} ({The forcing} 17. Rde1 $5 {leads to equality:} Bxb2+ 18. Kc2 Qd6 19. h5 Qa3 20. Be4 $1 Qxa2 21. Qb3 Qxb3+ 22. Kxb3 Bd7 $1 23. hxg6 (23. Kxa4 Rfb8 $11 {[%csl Ra4]}) 23... f5 24. Bf3 Rab8+ 25. Kc2 f4 26. Be4 Bg7 27. Rh7 Rfe8 28. Bxf4 (28. Bh6 Bxh6 29. Rxd7 Bg7 $11) 28... Nc5 $11) 17... Nc3 ({After} 17... Qd6 {, White can defend with} 18. Nb1 $1 Qd4 19. Rd2 Nc5 20. Bc2 Bg4 21. Rxd4 Bxf3 22. Rd2 Bxg2 23. Re1 Bd6 24. h5 $16 {, and after the exchange of queens, only Black's king remains in trouble.}) 18. Ne4 (18. Rde1 {is only good enough for equality:} Nxa2+ 19. Kd1 Nc3+ 20. Kc2 Na2 21. h5 Nb4+ 22. Kb1 Nxd3 23. Qxd3 Qd6 24. Qxd6 Bf5+ 25. Ka2 cxd6 26. Nf3 f6 27. Bh6 Rfb8 $11) 18... Nxd1 19. Rxd1 f5 (19... f6 20. Be3 f5 21. Nc5 {is similar.}) 20. Nc5 Qd6 21. Na4 Bf6 22. Be3 Rd8 23. Kc2 Be6 24. h5 Bf7 25. Bc1 $14 {Preventing Qa3. It's hard to suggest a plan for Black who has a weak king, a damaged structure and a minus pawn - plenty of compensation for the exchange.}) 10. g3 (10. Rh3 {can be answered with} O-O-O 11. Ra3 Nb4 12. Nc3 Qe6 13. Be3 Qf5 $1 14. Rc1 Qxe5 $13) 10... f6 (10... O-O-O 11. Bh3 $1 f6 12. O-O Nb6 13. b3 g5 (13... Qxe5 $6 14. Qxe5 fxe5 15. Bg5 Re8 16. a4 $1 $16 {Followed by a4-a5. Even though he is a pawn down, White is clearly better due to the pitiful placement of Black's pieces on the queenside and the strong pressure exerted by his bishops.}) 14. Qb2 $1 Bg7 (14... gxh4 15. exf6 {looks good for White,}) 15. a4 $1 Kb8 16. a5 Nc8 17. Nc3 gxh4 18. Ne4 f5 19. Bg5 Bxe5 20. Bxe7 Bxb2 21. Bxd8 fxe4 22. Ra2 (22. Bxh4 {Less clear is} Bxa1 23. Rxa1 d5 $13) 22... Rxd8 23. Rxb2 hxg3 24. fxg3 d5 $14 {Although Black's strong central pawns provide him with reasonable compensation for the exchange, White has the slightly better chances in this complicated ending.}) 11. b3 O-O-O 12. Bg2 Re8 13. Bb2 fxe5 14. Nd2 Nf6 15. O-O {A typical Scotch position has arisen in which White has plenty of compensation for the sacrificed e-pawn. Black's structure is damaged, the a6-bishop is out of play and the king does not look very safe.} Ng4 16. Rae1 d5 (16... g5 $5 {is another interesting attempt to gain immediate counterplay.} 17. f3 gxh4 18. fxg4 Qc5+ 19. Kh2 hxg4 20. Ne4 hxg3+ 21. Kxg3 Qe7 22. Nf6 Qd8 $1 23. Qxg4 Re6 24. Bxe5 Be7 25. Nxd7 Rg8 26. Bg7 Rxg7 27. Qxg7 Rxe1 28. Rxe1 Bh4+ 29. Kf4 Bxe1 30. Bxc6 Qh4+ $11 {, and at the end of this inhuman line, Black can force a perpetual.}) 17. f3 Nf6 18. Bxe5 Nd7 19. f4 Nxe5 20. fxe5 g5 $1 21. Nf3 (21. Rf6 gxh4 22. Rxc6 Bb7 $13) 21... gxh4 22. Nxh4 Qg5 23. Qf2 Kb8 24. Qf6 Bc5+ 25. Kh2 Rhg8 $11 {, and Black should be able to hold this endgame.}) 9. c4 (9. Bg5 {is an interesting alternative that forces Black to play very accurately:} Qc5 $1 10. c4 Qb4+ $1 11. Nd2 h6 12. Bf6 Nxf6 13. exf6+ Kd8 14. O-O-O Rb8 15. Nf3 (15. Nb3 Bd6 {is quite satisfactory for Black.}) 15... Bd6 16. Re1 Bf4+ 17. Kb1 d5 $13 {Now White's best chance seems to be} 18. h5 (18. Qe7+ {is premature:} Qxe7 19. fxe7+ Ke8 20. Bd3 h5 $11) 18... Bf5+ 19. Ka1 g5 20. Nd4 Bd7 21. Qe7+ Qxe7 22. fxe7+ Ke8 23. Bd3 dxc4 24. Bxc4 Rb4 25. b3 f6 26. a3 {And now Black should remove the dangerous bishop:} Rxc4 27. bxc4 Be5 28. Re4 c5 29. Rxe5 fxe5 30. Nf3 $11 {, with an equal position.}) 9... Ba6 (9... Qb4+ {is insufficient for equality:} 10. Nd2 Nf4 11. Qe3 Ne6 12. h5 $14) 10. Rh3 $5 {The rook is generally useful on the third rank and concretely intends to harass the bishop on a6. This Black should forego by removing his knight from the centre and attacking c4 immediately:} (10. Bg5 {is similar to 9.Bg5:} Qb4+ 11. Nd2 h6 12. Bf6 Nxf6 13. exf6+ Kd8 14. O-O-O Rb8 15. Nb3 Bd6 $132) 10... Nb6 11. b3 (11. Bg5 {again leads to unclear play after} Qb4+ 12. Qd2 Bxc4 13. Bf6 Rg8 14. Nc3 Be6 $13) 11... Bg7 (11... O-O-O $6 {is insufficient for equality:} 12. Bg5 Qb4+ 13. Nc3 Re8 ({The sacrifice} 13... Bg7 $6 14. Bxd8 Rxd8 15. O-O-O d5 16. f4 $16 {falls short as Black cannot easily activate his pieces without an unfavourable trade of rooks.}) 14. Bf6 Rg8 15. Qc2 {Threatening a2-a3, which Black should prevent.} Qa3 16. Be2 Be7 17. Bxe7 Rxe7 18. f4 d6 19. Rb1 $1 {Threatening to trap the queen.} Rge8 (19... dxe5 $2 20. b4 Bxc4 $8 21. Nd5 $16) 20. Ne4 Qb4+ 21. Qc3 Qxc3+ 22. Rxc3 f5 (22... dxe5 23. Nf6 Rd8 24. Re3 {wins back the pawn, remaining with the better pieces and better structure.}) 23. Nf6 Rf8 24. Kf2 dxe5 25. fxe5 Bb7 26. Re3 c5 $14 {White has the slightly better chances in this complicated ending.}) 12. Bg5 $1 (12. Bb2 $2 {is a mistake:} O-O-O 13. Nd2 {1-0 (129) Kacharava,N (2443)-Demchenko,A (2599) Chess.com INT 2021} d6 $17) 12... Qe6 ({The endgame after} 12... Qb4+ 13. Qd2 Qxd2+ 14. Nxd2 {is slightly better for White, for example} d6 (14... O-O 15. Bf6 Bxf6 16. exf6 Rfe8+ 17. Re3 Rxe3+ 18. fxe3 Bb7 (18... Re8 19. g4 $1 {Giving up the weak e-pawn to achieve g4-g5.}) 19. g4 c5 20. g5 $14) 15. c5 (15. O-O-O {also looks good.}) 15... Bxf1 16. Kxf1 Nd5 17. cxd6 cxd6 18. Rc1 Bxe5 19. Rxc6 h6 20. Be3 a5 $14) (12... Qc5 13. Bf6 O-O 14. Qe3 {leads to another slightly favourable endgame for White after} Qxe3+ 15. Rxe3 Bh6 16. Bg5 Bg7 17. Nc3 Rfe8 18. Bf6 Bh6 19. Re2 d5 20. exd6 cxd6 21. Ne4 $14) 13. Re3 (13. Bf6 $5 {is an interesting pawn sacrifice:} Bxf6 14. exf6 O-O 15. Qxe6 fxe6 16. Nd2 Rxf6 17. h5 Raf8 18. Ne4 Rf5 19. hxg6 hxg6 20. Bd3 Kg7 $44) (13. Nc3 {also gives White sufficient compensation for the pawn after} O-O 14. O-O-O Qxe5 15. Qxe5 Bxe5 16. Re3 Rfe8 $44) 13... O-O 14. Nc3 d6 (14... Rae8 15. O-O-O h6 16. Bf6 d5 17. Qe1 $14 {is unpleasant for Black who cannot take on f6, while dxc4 can always be answered with Ne4, threatening Nc5.}) (14... d5 {gives White the extra option} 15. cxd5 (15. exd6 Qxd6 {transposes.}) 15... cxd5 16. Qxa6 d4 17. Re4 dxc3 18. O-O-O $13) 15. exd6 (15. Ne4 {Leads to an unclear position after} dxe5 16. Nc5 Qc8 17. h5 h6 18. hxg6 fxg6 19. Qc2 e4 20. O-O-O hxg5 21. Qxe4 $13) 15... Qxd6 16. Qd2 {Here White has some options:} (16. Rc1 Bxc3+ (16... f6 $5 17. Re6 Qh2 18. Be3 Nd7 $13 {may be playable but looks dangerous for Black in practice.}) 17. Rcxc3 Nd5 18. Be7 Nxe7 19. Rxe7 Rad8 20. Ree3 Qf6 $11 {Engines consider this position to be equal but White can certainly play on and try to capitalise on his better structure.}) (16. Rd1 {forces Black to part with his bishop and find a sequence of further accurate moves:} Bxc3+ $1 17. Rxc3 Nd5 18. Rcd3 Rae8 19. Be3 Qb4+ 20. Qd2 Nxe3 21. Rxe3 Rxe3+ 22. fxe3 Qe7 23. Qd4 c5 24. Qf4 $11) 16... Rfe8 17. O-O-O (17. Rc1 {is an interesting alternative, intending to keep the tension with} Bd4 18. Re2 c5 19. Kd1 Rxe2 20. Bxe2 Re8 21. Bf3 $11) {Now Black can force a draw:} 17... Qa3+ 18. Kc2 h6 19. Rxe8+ (19. Bxh6 Na4 $1 $11) 19... Rxe8 20. Bxh6 Na4 $1 21. Nxa4 (21. bxa4 Rb8 22. Rb1 Rxb1 23. Kxb1 Bxh6 24. Qxh6 Qxc3 $11) 21... Qxa2+ 22. Kc1 Qa3+ $11 {Black forces a perpetual.} *

