1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. h4 f6 {One of the most important lines. Black attacks the central pawn immediately.} 9. c4 Ba6 ({Clearly insufficient is} 9... Nb6 $6 10. exf6 Qxe2+ 11. Bxe2 gxf6 12. O-O $16 {1-0 (24) Morozevich,A (2676)-Anand,V (2779)/Doha QAT 2016/The Week in Chess 1156 (24) Black's pawn structure is severely damaged and the king can become a target.}) ({After} 9... Qb4+ $6 10. Kd1 $1 {, White's king stands surprisingly safe while Black faces something like a double attack against d5 and f6.}) 10. Rh3 $1 {[%cal Gh3a3] The idea behind White's 8th move. The rook can harass Black's bishop on a6 and is generally well-placed on the third rank.} (10. exf6 Nxf6 $11 {does not achieve anything.}) 10... O-O-O {Black has several serious alternatives:} (10... fxe5 {Taking the pawn is of course critical.} 11. Bg5 Nf6 {Blocking the attack against the queen looks best, but now White can use the e3-square:} (11... Qb4+ $6 {only loses valuable time after} 12. Nc3 $16) (11... Qd6 $6 {is met with the thematic} 12. Ra3 $1 Qb4+ 13. Nc3 Nxc3 (13... Bd6 $6 14. Rc1 Bxc4 15. Qxc4 Qxc4 16. Bxc4 Bxa3 17. bxa3 $16 {The two bishops are too strong.}) 14. Rxc3 ({Less clear is} 14. Qxe5+ Kf7 15. Qf5+ Kg8 16. Rb3 Qc5 $11) 14... Be7 15. a3 (15. O-O-O Bxg5+ 16. hxg5 Qe7 $44) (15. Qxe5 $6 O-O $36 {just helps Black to activate his forces and develop serious counterplay.}) 15... Qd6 16. Rd1 Qe6 17. Re3 {White centralises his forces while winning time on Black's queen.} Bd6 $1 {Black's only move and rather difficult to find, as the bishop had just been moved to e7.} (17... d6 $2 {leads to problems after} 18. Qf3 $1 Bb7 19. Rb3 $1 e4 (19... O-O-O $2 {loses quickly to} 20. Bxe7 Qxe7 21. c5 Qe6 22. Rxb7 Kxb7 23. Ba6+ $18) 20. Qc3 $16) 18. Bf4 O-O 19. Bxe5 Qf7 $14 {At least in practice, White's position looks slightly preferable.}) 12. Re3 O-O-O (12... Qb4+ $2 13. Nd2 $16) ({Clinging to the pawn leads to problems:} 12... d6 $2 13. Qf3 $1 e4 ({Or} 13... Bb7 14. Rb3 O-O-O 15. Nd2 {[%cal Gc4c5]} Qe6 16. c5 d5 17. Qc3 $18 {, followed by Qb4.}) 14. Qd1 Bb7 15. Nc3 $16 {Black cannot defend all of his weaknesses.}) 13. Ra3 ({After} 13. Nd2 $5 {, the forced line} h6 14. Ra3 hxg5 15. Rxa6 Kb7 16. Ra4 Rxh4 17. g3 Rh1 18. Nb3 Rb8 $1 {[%cal Gb7c8] 0-1 (75) Lyell,M (2302)-Mouhamad, J (2272) Budapest 2020} 19. c5 Kc8 20. Qa6+ Kd8 21. Qxa7 Rc8 $13 {leads to a very unclear position with chances for both sides.}) 13... Bb7 (13... Qb4+ $2 {forces Black into a bad endgame after} 14. Nc3 Bxc4 (14... Bb7 15. Rb3 Qa5 16. Bd2 $18) 15. Qxc4 Qxc4 16. Bxc4 Bxa3 17. Ba6+ Kb8 18. bxa3 Ka8 19. Rc1 $16) 14. Nc3 $5 (14. Rxa7 Qe6 15. Nd2 Bb4 $13 {1/2  (54) Cheparinov,I (2718)-Aravindh,C (2581)/Abu Dhabi UAE 2018/The Week in Chess 1240}) (14. Nd2 Qe6) 14... d5 $5 (14... Qe6 15. Rb3 Bc5 {Black has to play actively.} (15... Be7 $6 16. g3 $16 {White has strong long-term compensation and pressure against Black's king's position.}) 16. Na4 $1 Bd4 17. O-O-O c5 18. Rxd4 $1 exd4 19. Qxe6 dxe6 20. Nxc5 {White has good compensation, for example} Bc6 21. g3 $1 h6 (21... Nd7 22. Nxe6 Rde8 23. Nxd4 Nc5 24. Re3 $14) 22. Bxf6 gxf6 23. Bh3 f5 24. Nxe6 Rd6 25. Nf4 (25. Bxf5 $2 Bd7) 25... Rf6 26. Ra3 Re8 27. Kd2 Kb8 $44 {1/2-1/2 (38) Bruno,R (2200) -Grammatica,A (2330) LSS email 2020}) 15. cxd5 cxd5 16. Rb3 $1 {Now White has serious threats against Black's king.} (16. Rxa7 Qb4 $13 {leads to very unclear play.}) 16... c5 (16... h6 $2 {gives White a strong attack after} 17. Qb5 $1 c6 18. Qa4 Rd7 (18... hxg5 19. Qxa7 {[%cal Gb3b7]} Rd7 20. Ba6 $18) 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. Rc1 Kb8 21. Nd1 $1 $18 {[%cal Gc1c6] 1-0 (43) Cvak,R (2350)-Farr,D (1632) LSS email 2020}) (16... c6 17. Rc1 Kb8 18. Na4 Qc7 19. Nc5 Bxc5 20. Rxc5 {And now Black has to defend actively:} Ne4 $1 21. Bxd8 Rxd8 22. Rc2 c5 {, with compensation for the exchange. A possible continuation is} 23. Qb5 Rc8 24. Ra3 c4 25. Qb4 Qb6 26. Qxb6 axb6 27. Re2 {[%cal Gf2f3]} b5 28. f3 b4 29. Ra5 c3 30. bxc3 bxc3 31. fxe4 c2 32. Rxc2 Rxc2 33. exd5 Kc7 $11 {, with a drawish endgame.}) 17. Rd1 $1 c4 (17... d4 $6 {is bad because of} 18. g3 $16 {, and Black cannot take the knight:} dxc3 19. Bh3+ Kb8 20. Rxd8+ Qxd8 21. Bg2) 18. Rb5 Qe6 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. Rdxd5 $5 (20. Nxd5 {leads to a draw after} Bxd5 21. Qd2 Be7 22. Rxd5 Rxd5 23. Qxd5 Bb4+ 24. Ke2 Qxd5 25. Rxd5 Rd8 $11) 20... Bxd5 21. Nxd5 Qxd5 $1 ({After} 21... Qc6 {, White can keep some pressure by playing} 22. Qg4+ f5 23. Qxf5+ Qd7 24. g4 Qxf5 25. gxf5 $14) 22. Rxd5 Bb4+ 23. Kd1 Rxd5+ 24. Kc1 Rhd8 25. Qg4+ (25. a3 Rd1+ $11 {is another draw.}) 25... Kb8 26. Be2 Ba5 $11 {White can try to win h7 and push his h-pawn, but also has to deal with Black's very active rooks. The position is equal.}) (10... Nb6 $5 {Anticipating White's idea to play Ra3. Now White has several options:} 11. exf6 $1 {This is probably White's best chance to play for an advantage.} (11. Re3 $5 f5 $1 {Keeping the e-file closed and threatening two of White's pawns. Other moves fail to equalise.} (11... O-O-O 12. Qc2 $1 Qe6 13. a4 $1 $36) 12. b3 ({Or} 12. Nd2 Qxh4 13. Rh3 Qd4 14. Rd3 Qg4 $13) 12... Qxh4 $1 (12... O-O-O $6 13. g3 $14) 13. Bb2 O-O-O (13... Bb4+ $6 14. Nd2) (13... Bc5 $5 14. Rh3 Qf4 $13) 14. Rh3 (14. Nd2 $6 Bc5) 14... Qg4 15. Nd2 $44 {White has full compensation for the pawn, but probably not more than that.}) (11. Nd2 fxe5 (11... O-O-O $6 {gives White the advantage after} 12. Ra3 $1 Bb7 13. Ra5 $14 {, strongly activating the rook and keeping e5 protected.}) 12. Re3 d6 13. g3 {White calmly relies on his positional advantages outweighing the sacrificed pawn.} Qd7 $1 (13... O-O-O $2 14. Ra3 $16 {is very dangerous for Black.}) 14. Ra3 Bc8 15. c5 Nd5 16. Ne4 Be7 17. Qh5+ g6 18. Qd1 O-O (18... Nf6 $5) 19. Bh6 Rf7 20. Qa4 Qe8 {1-0 (42) Jones,G (2665) -Esipenko,A (2705) Chartres 2022 , and now most promising seems} 21. O-O-O Bf5 22. f3 $44 {, with good compensation for the pawn.}) 11... Qxe2+ 12. Bxe2 Bxc4 13. Re3+ Kd8 (13... Be6 14. fxg7 Bxg7 15. Bg4 Nd5 16. Re2 Rb8 (16... O-O 17. Bxe6+ dxe6 18. g3 Nb4 19. Nc3 Nd3+ 20. Kf1 Bxc3 21. bxc3 e5 22. Bh6 Rf6 23. Bg5 Rd6 24. Rb1 $16 {1/2 (45) Cheparinov,I (2691)-Ernst,S (2540)/Caleta ENG 2019/The Week in Chess 1264}) 17. g3 O-O 18. Bxe6+ dxe6 19. Kf1 $14 {Black has some activity, but his pawn structure is extremely compromised.}) (13... Kf7 $6 {gives White the better chances due to Black's bad king's position:} 14. fxg7 Bxg7 15. Bh5+ Kg8 (15... Kf8 {1/2-1/2 (144) Cheparinov,I (2667)-Jones,G (2702) Hengshui 2019} 16. Nc3 $16) 16. Rg3 Bf7 17. Bh6 Bg6 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Be2 $14) 14. fxg7 Bxg7 15. Nc3 a5 $5 16. Re4 Bxe2 {1/2-1/2 (49) Brodsky,D (2484) -Schitco,I (2484) Saint Louis 2022 , and now best is} 17. Kxe2 a4 18. a3 {The computer now claims equality after} Rg8 $11 {, but in practice, this endgame certainly looks more pleasant for White.}) 11. Ra3 $1 {Now Black is forced to find a couple of "only moves":} Nb4 12. Ra4 $1 {[%cal Ga2a3] Threatening a2-a3.} Qxe5 (12... Bb7 $2 13. a3 Na6 14. b4 $18 {1-0 (25) Chigaev, M (2560)-Pogonina,N (2478)/Moscow RUS 2018/The Week in Chess 1216 (25)}) (12... Qe6 13. a3 Bxc4 14. Qxc4 Qxc4 15. Bxc4 Nc2+ 16. Kd1 Nxa1 17. exf6 gxf6 18. b4 $16 {is another endgame in which White's minor pieces are clearly better than the rook.}) 13. Qxe5 fxe5 14. Bg5 $1 Nc2+ (14... Re8 {is also playable, but White looks better in all lines:} 15. Kd1 Bb7 16. a3 Na6 17. b4 {Black is a pawn up, but his pieces on the queenside look very awkward.} Nb8 (17... Be7 18. Nd2 $14) (17... h6 18. Bd2 $14) (17... d5 18. cxd5 Nb8 19. dxc6 Nxc6 20. Be3 Nd4 21. Nd2 Kb8 22. g3 $16) 18. Rxa7 Na6 (18... d5 $6 19. Nc3 d4 20. Ne4 c5 21. f3 $16) 19. Nc3 ({Also possible are} 19. Be3 $5 Kb8 20. Kc2 Bc8 21. b5) ({and} 19. c5 Nxc5 20. bxc5 Bxc5 21. Ra4 Rhf8 22. f3 Bd4 23. Ra2 c5 $44) 19... Kb8 20. Be3 Bc8 (20... c5 $2 21. Rxb7+ Kxb7 22. b5 Nb8 23. g3 $18) 21. Rb1 Bc5 (21... c5 $6 22. Rxa6 Bxa6 23. bxc5+ Kc8 24. g3 $16) 22. Bxc5 (22. Rxa6 Bxe3) 22... Nxc5 23. Ra5 Nb7 24. Ra4 Rhf8 25. Ke1 e4 26. Be2 $14) 15. Kd1 Nxa1 16. Bxd8 Kxd8 17. Rxa6 Bc5 {Now White can secure a clear advantage if he manages to win the trapped knight, but with accurate moves Black can develop sufficient counterplay:} 18. f3 Rf8 $1 {[%cal Gf8f4]} 19. Ra5 $1 (19. Nd2 {is also possible but easier to defend for Black:} Rf4 20. Ra5 Bf2 ({Or} 20... Bb4 21. Rxe5 Rd4 22. Re2 Rxh4 23. Ne4 d5 24. cxd5 cxd5 25. Nf2 Rc4 $11) 21. Rxe5 Rxh4 22. Re2 Bg3 $11) 19... Bd4 20. Nd2 ({Or} 20. Nc3 Rf4 21. Ne2 Rxh4 22. Nxd4 exd4 23. Kd2 Rh1 24. Bd3 Rg1 25. Rg5 g6 $11 {, and neither side can make serious progress.}) 20... Bxb2 (20... Rf4 {can now be answered with} 21. g3) 21. Rxa7 Ke7 $1 (21... Rf4 {fails to equalise after} 22. Rb7 Bd4 23. g3 Rf6 24. Rb8+ Ke7 25. Rg8 Rg6 26. g4 e4 $1 27. Nxe4 c5 28. Ra8 Rb6 29. Bd3 Rb2 $14 {White has slowly consolidated his position while the knight still remains trapped on a1.}) 22. Rxc7 Bd4 ({Also good is} 22... Rb8 $5 23. Bd3 g6 $11 {, and Black should be able to defend.}) 23. Bd3 g6 ({More precise is probably} 23... Kd8 $1 {, ejecting the rook from its active position.} 24. Rb7 Kc8 25. Rb4 Kc7 $11) 24. Rb7 Ra8 25. Bb1 Ra4 26. Rb8 {The position is objectively equal, but the situation of his knight makes it more difficult to play for Black.} (26. g4 $5 {is an interesting alternative, trying to create a dangerous passed pawn on the kingside.}) 26... e4 $1 {Now Black can further simplify the position into a draw:} (26... h5 $2 {gave White a winning advantage after} 27. Bxg6 d5 28. cxd5 cxd5 29. Rb5 Kf6 30. Bh7 $18 {1/2-1/2 (60) Erigaisi,A (2675)-Van Foreest, L (2572) Sharjah 2022}) 27. fxe4 (27. Nxe4 Be5 $11 {, followed by Rxc4.}) 27... Bc3 28. Nf3 Rxc4 $11 *

