1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. h4 d6 {This is a very solid option for Black, challenging the e5-pawn and preventing White's idea to play Rh3.} 9. c4 Nb6 ({After} 9... Ba6 $6 {, White achieves a clear advantage with} 10. Bg5 f6 $8 11. exf6 Qxe2+ 12. Bxe2 Nxf6 13. Nc3 Be7 14. O-O-O $16 {The bishop on a6 is obviously misplaced now and White has the better structure.}) 10. exd6 cxd6 ({Black's alternative is to exchange queens:} 10... Qxe2+ 11. Bxe2 {, and now he faces another choice:} Bxd6 {Black now intends to castle quickly and develop some counterplay to compensate for his inferior structure.} (11... cxd6 {By taking with the pawn, Black accepts a slightly inferior endgame without any winning chances. Now White has two good moves:} 12. Bf3 $5 (12. Nc3 Be6 13. Bf3 $1 (13. b3 d5 $11 {, followed by Bb4, gives Black enough activity to equalise.}) 13... Rc8 14. b3 d5 15. cxd5 Bb4 ({Or} 15... Nxd5 16. Nxd5 cxd5 17. O-O Bc5 18. Rd1 O-O 19. Bf4 $14) 16. Bd2 Nxd5 17. Nxd5 Bxd2+ 18. Kxd2 cxd5 19. b4 $14 {, with a stable advantage in this IQP endgame.}) 12... d5 ({Or} 12... Bd7 13. b3) 13. cxd5 Nxd5 (13... cxd5 $6 {Keeping a passive knight on the board does not help Black's defence.} 14. Nc3 Be6 {1/2 (29) Nestorovic,N (2476)-Panchanathan,M (2480)/ Charlotte USA 2018/ The Week in Chess 1232 (29)} 15. O-O $16 {White will play Rd1 and a2-a4, with very serious pressure against Black's isolated d-pawn.}) 14. Nc3 Be6 15. Nxd5 cxd5 16. Be3 Bb4+ 17. Ke2 $14 {Again White has a stable advantage and can play for a win without taking any risks.}) 12. Nc3 O-O {Castling kingside gives Black better chances to equalise. Now White has a choice:} (12... Be6 13. b3 O-O-O (13... a5 14. Bf3 {only helps White.}) 14. Bb2 Rhe8 15. O-O $14 {Inarkiev,E (2680)-Abdusattorov,N (2540)/ Sharjah UAE 2018. White has consolidated and is slightly better due to his structural advantage.}) 13. Bd2 $5 $146 {With this new move White takes the sting out of any Bb4 ideas and will be ready to play b2-b3 whenever c4 is under pressure.} (13. Be3 {This natural move was played in all previous games. White develops a piece and threatens c4-c5.} Bb4 14. O-O {Black's best chance is the somewhat counter-intuitive} (14. O-O-O Bxc3 15. bxc3 Be6 16. c5 Nc4 17. Bf4 {, and now Black should activate one of his rooks:} Rfb8 $1 18. Bxc7 Rb5 19. Rd4 Rxc5 $11 {Black's active pieces should be enough to counterbalance White's pair of bishops.}) (14. Rc1 Na4 15. a3 Bxc3+ 16. bxc3 Bf5 17. O-O Nb2 {, and now White can keep a small advantage by preserving his pair of bishops with} 18. Bf3 $14) 14... Be6 $1 $146 {, which fails to pin the c-pawn but on the other hand keeps the bishop protected from being the victim of a pin on the f1-a6 diagonal.} (14... Bxc3 {fails to equalise after} 15. bxc3 Ba6 16. Rfb1 $1 Bxc4 (16... Nxc4 {puts the knight into a nasty pin. After} 17. Bf4 {, White already threatens Rb4.}) 17. Rxb6 Bxe2 18. Rxc6 $14 {White's active pieces offer him reasonable chances to play for a win in this simplified position.}) ({Most games continued} 14... Ba6 $6 15. Rfc1 Bxc4 16. Bf3 $14 {, with a pleasant endgame advantage for White as Black cannot hold on to his extra pawn.}) 15. c5 Nc4 16. Bxc4 Bxc4 17. Rfc1 Rfd8 18. a3 Bxc3 19. Rxc3 Bd5 $11 {This endgame is very drawish. The bishop is very well positioned on d5. Black will play a7-a5 and place a rook on the b-file, which should prevent White from making any progress.}) 13... Re8 ({After} 13... Be6 14. b3 a5 15. Bf3 a4 16. O-O $14 {, Black can exchange one of his weaknesses but has a hard time dealing with the pressure against c6.}) 14. O-O Bf5 $1 ({Again,} 14... Be6 {can be easily answered with} 15. b3 $14 {, followed by Bf3.}) 15. Rfe1 {Now White would like to eject the bishop f5 from its active diagonal with g2-g4, so Black's best is} h6 {, securing a retreat square.} 16. Rad1 Nd7 17. b3 Ne5 {The point of Black's play: The knight will come to d3. Still, Black has to find some very difficult moves to equalise:} 18. Na4 Nd3 19. Bxd3 Bxd3 20. Rxe8+ Rxe8 21. Be3 Bc2 $1 22. Rc1 Bd3 23. Bxa7 Bxc4 $1 24. Be3 ({Or} 24. bxc4 Ra8) 24... Bd5 25. Nc5 f6 $11 {The passed a-pawn may still give White some practical chances, but objectively the game is equal.}) 11. Be3 {This prevents a queen swap and keeps the option to develop the knight to d2.} ({After} 11. Nc3 {, Black can equalise with} Be6 $1 12. b3 d5 $1 13. cxd5 Nxd5 14. Bb2 ({Or} 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 $11 {1/2-1/2 (63) Zherebukh,Y (2620)-Stevic,H (2570) chess.com INT 2020}) 14... Qb4 15. Qc4 Qxc4 16. Bxc4 Bb4 17. Bxd5 Bxd5 18. O-O-O Bxc3 19. Bxc3 f6 20. Rd4 Kf7 21. f3 Rhe8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (51) Nepomniachtchi,I (2784)-Aronian,L (2781) chess24.com INT 2020}) 11... d5 $1 {As a consequence of his previous move, White is able to keep the tension.} (11... Be6 12. Qc2 $1 (12. Nd2 Qd7 $13 {, preparing d6-d5 and Be7, is satisfactory for Black.}) 12... g6 (12... Qd7 $6 {is weaker here:} 13. Nd2 d5 14. O-O-O d4 15. Ne4 c5 16. Bf4 Be7 17. Bd3 $16 {1-0 (68) Cheparinov,I  (2693) -Alekseev,E (2617)/Batumi GEO 2018/The Week in Chess 1220 (68)}) (12... Qc7 13. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Gf1d3] , followed by Bd3 and 0-0, is slightly better for White.}) 13. Qc3 $1 {A time-consuming manoeuvre, but being denied short castling, Black's king will be a target for a very long time.} Rg8 {[%cal Gf8g7]} 14. Be2 $5 $146 (14. Bg5 {was previously played but Black equalised after} Bg7 15. Bxe7 Bxc3+ 16. Nxc3 Kxe7 17. b3 a5 18. Kd2 a4 $11 {1/2 (18) Ivanisevic, I (2611)-Georgiev,K (2631)/Mali Losinj CRO 2017/The Week in Chess 1195}) 14... Bg7 ({Now} 14... d5 $2 {is a bad idea, opening the position when the king has no safe shelter.} 15. O-O $1 Bg7 (15... dxc4 16. Nd2 $16) (15... Nxc4 16. Bxc4 dxc4 17. Nd2 Qb4 18. Qc2 O-O-O 19. Rac1 $16) 16. Qa5 $1 Bxb2 (16... d4 17. Bg5 f6 18. Bf4 $16) 17. Bxb6 Bxa1 18. cxd5 Bxd5 19. Re1 $1 {, and Black already has no defence, for example} Qxh4 20. Nd2 Kd7 (20... Be5 21. Nf3 $18) 21. Be3 Be5 22. Nf3 Qh5 23. Nxe5+ Qxe5 24. Bc4 $18 {[%cal Ge1d1] Rd1 is a threat and the king is just too open.}) 15. Qc2 {Provoking Black's next move.} Bf5 16. Qc1 Na4 ({After} 16... O-O-O 17. Nc3 $14 {, Black's king remains vulnerable.}) 17. Nc3 Nxc3 18. bxc3 Qe5 19. Bd4 Qe4 20. Bxg7 Rxg7 21. O-O Kf8 {Now White must play very actively to prevent Black from coordinating his pieces and reaching equality:} 22. Bf3 $5 Qxc4 23. Rd1 Qc5 24. Qf4 Rd8 25. Re1 Kg8 26. Rad1 $14 {[%csl Rg7] The rook on g7 remains a problem for Black that is not easily solved.}) (11... Qe6 {Black prepares Be7 and 0-0.} 12. Nc3 Be7 13. O-O-O O-O {Now White should play} 14. Bg5 $1 {, to weaken the defence of d6 or force the following concession:} f6 15. Bf4 d5 (15... Rd8 16. Qf3 $36 {, followed by Bd3 and Rhe1, puts a lot of pressure on Black's position.}) 16. cxd5 Nxd5 {Here White can force an IQP endgame with} 17. Nxd5 ({Also good is} 17. Qf3 Nxf4 18. Qxf4 Qe5 {1/2 (56) Firouzja,A (2618)-Karthikeyan,M (2560)/ Moscow RUS 2019/The Week in Chess 1268 (56)} 19. Bc4+ Kh8 20. Qxe5 fxe5 21. f3 $14) 17... cxd5 18. Qxe6+ Bxe6 19. Ba6 $1 $14 {Black's rooks are denied the squares b8 and c8. The position may be close to equality, but Black has no winning chances and is forced to defend accurately.}) 12. Nd2 $1 {As a consequence of his previous move, White is able to keep the tension.} (12. Bxb6 {gives Black easy equality after} axb6 13. cxd5 Qxe2+ 14. Bxe2 Bb4+ 15. Nc3 cxd5 $11) 12... dxc4 ({Keeping the tension does not work for Black here:} 12... Be6 13. c5 $1 Nd7 14. Qa6 $1 Qd8 15. b4 $5 (15. Nb3 {is also very good for White.}) 15... Be7 16. Nf3 O-O 17. Be2 Qb8 18. a3 Ne5 19. O-O $14 {, with a typical blockade that is very much in White's favour.}) 13. g3 {White quickly finishes his development before collecting the weak pawn(s).} Be6 ({The active} 13... Nd5 {is met by calm development:} 14. Bg2 Qe6 (14... Nxe3 $6 {Exchanging his only developed piece doesn't work out for Black.} 15. Bxc6+ Bd7 16. Bxd7+ Qxd7 17. Qxe3+ Be7 18. O-O $16) 15. Qxc4 $14) (13... c3 