1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. h4 Qe6 {This can be considered the mainline after 8.h4. Black prepares to develop his kingside immediately.} 9. Nd2 ({Also possible are} 9. g3) ({and} 9. c4) 9... a5 $1 {Black's best move, but he has many alternatives:} (9... Nb4 $6 {is insufficient due to} 10. Nf3 {, and now} Ba6 {is met by} (10... Rb8 11. a3 Na2 12. Bd2 Rxb2 13. Qe3 $16 {White can follow up with Nd4 and/or Bd3. With the knight stuck on a2, Black isn't going to enjoy his extra pawn very much.}) (10... Qg6 11. Nd4 {[%cal Gh4h5] Now h4-h5 even Threatens to win the queen.} h5 (11... c5 12. h5 $16 {takes the pressure off c2, after which Black's knight manoeuvre turns out to be pointless.}) 12. a3 Ba6 (12... c5 13. Qf3 $16) 13. c4 c5 14. axb4 cxd4 15. Bd2 $16) 11. c4 {, as usual. Again Black faces difficult problems: Somewhat better is} c5 (11... d5 $2 12. a3 Bxc4 13. Qd1 Bxf1 (13... Na6 14. b4) 14. Kxf1 Na6 15. b4 $16 {1-0 (20) Morozevich,A (2683)-Sychev,K  (2445)/Moscow 2016. White will follow up with Qa4 and Nd4, with a huge advantage.}) 12. a3 ({Also interesting is} 12. Ng5 $5 Qe7 13. Bf4 $14 {, and the knight can later move to e4.}) 12... Nc6 13. Bd2 O-O-O 14. O-O-O Be7 15. Bc3 Rhe8 16. Re1 $14 {The pawn on e5 paralyses Black's position. White can follow up with g2-g3 and Bh3 or Qe4 and Bd3.}) (9... f6 $6 {Offers White a very pleasant endgame after} 10. exf6 Qxe2+ 11. Bxe2 Nxf6 12. O-O $14 {[%cal Gf1e1]}) (9... Be7 {is solid but somewhat passive.} 10. Nf3 f6 {Otherwise, Nd4 is very strong, even winning the queen after 10...0-0??} 11. Bd2 $1 {Preparing 0-0-0.} O-O (11... fxe5 12. Qxe5 Qxe5+ 13. Nxe5 Bf6 14. O-O-O $16 {[%cal Gd1e1] is again a very good endgame for White.}) 12. Qe4 ({Also good is the simple} 12. O-O-O Nb6 13. Kb1 $14) 12... fxe5 ({Or} 12... f5 13. Qa4 Nb6 14. Qa5 $14) 13. Bd3 Nf6 (13... g6 14. h5 $36) 14. Qxe5 d5 15. Qxe6+ Bxe6 16. O-O Bd6 17. Rfe1 Rae8 18. Bc3 $14 {As usual in these lines, the endgame is promising and completely risk-free for White.}) (9... d6 $5 {A solid move, but at least for practical purposes, White should keep the slightly better chances in the following typical endgames.} 10. exd6 Bxd6 (10... Nb4 11. Kd1 $14) (10... cxd6 11. Nc4 $14) 11. Nc4 Bc5 {Now White has a choice:} (11... O-O $2 12. Qxe6 Bxe6 13. Nxd6 cxd6 14. Bd2 Bg4 15. f3 Rfe8+ 16. Kf2 Be6 17. c4 Nb6 18. b3 $16 {1-0  (72) Aravindh,C (2581)-Kravtsiv,M (2654)/Abu Dhabi UAE 2018/The Week in Chess 1240 (72)}) 12. a3 (12. Bd2 $146 O-O 13. O-O-O Qxe2 14. Bxe2 Ba6 $1 (14... Bxf2 15. Na5 $36) 15. Bf1 ({Or} 15. f3 Nb6 16. Nxb6 axb6 17. Bxa6 Rxa6 $11) (15. Rhf1 Nb6 $11) 15... Bxc4 ({Also sufficient for a draw is} 15... Bxf2 16. Na5 Bxf1 17. Rdxf1 Bb6 18. Nxc6 Rae8 $11) 16. Bxc4 Bxf2 $11 {White has compensation but no more than that.}) 12... O-O 13. Qxe6 Bxe6 14. Bd3 Rfe8 (14... a5 15. O-O Rfb8 {1/2-1/2 (60) Tsydypov,Z (2552)-Deac,B (2625) lichess. org INT 2021 , and now White's best chance is} 16. Re1 a4 17. Ne5 Rb6 18. Be4 h6 19. Bf3 $14) 15. O-O a5 (15... Bd4 16. Na5 $14 {[%csl Ga5]}) 16. Rb1 $146 (16. Bd2 a4 $11) (16. Ne5 Bc8 $1) (16. Re1 Nb6 17. Ne5 Bd5 18. Be3 Bd6 19. Bd4 c5 20. Bc3 c4 21. Bf1 Na4 22. Bd4 c5 23. Bxc4 Bxe5 24. Bxd5 Bxd4 25. Bc6 Rxe1+ 26. Rxe1 Rd8 27. Bxa4 Bxb2 $11 {Caruana-Robson USA-ch,2019}) 16... a4 (16... Nb6 $6 17. Nxa5 $14) 17. Re1 Nf6 (17... Bd4 18. Bd2 $14) (17... Nb6 18. Be3 $14 {, for example} Bxc4 19. Bxc5 Bxd3 20. cxd3 {, and White keeps some pressure thanks to his slightly better minor piece and structure.}) 18. Be3 Bxe3 (18... Bxc4 19. Bxc5 Bxd3 20. cxd3 $14) 19. Nxe3 h5 20. f3 $14 {[%cal Gg1f2]}) (9... Bb7 {This is not the ideal square for the bishop:} 10. c4 Nf4 (10... Nb4 11. Nb3 $14) 11. Qe3 Qg4 (11... Ng6 12. f4 $14) 12. g3 Ne6 (12... c5 $6 {loses material after} 13. Qxf4 Qxf4 14. gxf4 Bxh1 15. f3 $16) 13. Bh3 Qd4 14. Qe2 $14 {White will castle and play Nb3 or Nf3, after which Black will miss some of the tempi that he spent with his queen.}) (9... Rb8 {Black isn't threatening anything, so White can spend a tempo on} 10. a3 $1 {, preventing any Nb4- or Bb4-ideas.} Be7 (10... d6 11. exd6 Bxd6 12. Nc4 $14) 11. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3d4] Again threatening Nd4 and forcing} f6 12. g3 fxe5 (12... c5 13. Bh3 f5 14. O-O Ba6 15. c4 $16 {Black has several weaknesses and his pieces will be passive after White plays b2-b3.}) 13. Bh3 Qd6 14. c4 O-O $1 15. O-O $1 $36 ({Taking the piece gives Black a dangerous initiative:} 15. cxd5 cxd5 {, followed by Ba6 or e5-e4.})) 10. g3 $1 (10. c4 Nb6 $132 {, followed by Bb4 and Ba6, gives Black good counterplay.}) 10... Nb4 $1 {Again Black has other moves:} (10... Ba6 $6 11. c4 Bb4 (11... Nb6 12. b3 $16) (11... Nb4 12. Bh3 f5 (12... Qg6 $2 {loses to Ne4, threatening both h4-h5 and a2-a3.} 13. Ne4 $1 $18 {1-0 (55) Cheparinov,I (2667)-Svane,R (2615) Krasnaya Polyana 2021}) 13. O-O Be7 14. b3 $16 {Black's pieces on the queenside are completely pointless.}) 12. Bh3 Qe7 13. O-O O-O 14. Nf3 Nb6 (14... f6 $6 15. e6 $16) 15. b3 d5 16. Bf5 (16. Nd4 dxc4 17. Nf5 {looks very dangerous for Black, but only leads to a draw after} Qe8 18. Qg4 Qxe5 19. Bf4 Qf6 20. Bg5 Qe5 21. Bf4 $11) 16... h6 ({After} 16... dxc4 $6 {, White has the standard sacrifice} 17. Bxh7+ {, which Black cannot accept. Play should continue} Kh8 18. Be4 cxb3 19. Bd3 Bxd3 20. Qxd3 $40) ({Also bad is} 16... g6 $2 {due to} 17. Bd3 $16 {, threatening Bg5-f6.}) 17. Rd1 (17. Nd4 {leads to a draw after} Bc3 18. Bxh6 gxh6 19. Qg4+ Kh8 20. Qf4 $11) 17... dxc4 18. Qe4 $44 {White has good compensation for the sacrificed material, with ideas like Qg4 and Nd4.}) (10... f6 11. c4 ({The endgame after} 11. exf6 Qxe2+ 12. Bxe2 Nxf6 13. O-O Bc5 14. Nc4 Ba6 15. Re1 O-O 16. Be3 Bxe3 17. Nxe3 Bxe2 18. Rxe2 Rfb8 19. b3 a4 $11 {is slightly more pleasant for White but objectively equal.}) 11... Nb6 (11... Nb4 $6 12. Nf3 Bc5 13. Bh3 Qe7 14. a3 Na6 15. exf6 gxf6 16. Qxe7+ Kxe7 17. Bd2 $16 {1-0 (74) Wei Yi (2732)-Wagner,D  (2581) chess.com INT 2020 Black has many weaknesses and the knight on a6 is obviously misplaced.}) 12. exf6 {, and now best is} d5 $1 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Nb3 gxf6 ({Or} 14... Bb4+ 15. Bd2 $14) 15. Bd2 $14 {White keeps a small advantage due to his better structure.}) (10... Bc5 $146 11. c4 (11. Bh3 f5 $13) ({and} 11. Ne4 Bd4 $13 {are satisfactory for Black.}) 11... Nb6 12. Bh3 Qe7 13. O-O O-O 14. Nf3 f6 (14... d5 15. Bxc8 Raxc8 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. Bf4 $14 {, followed by Rc1 and possibly Qb5.}) 15. b3 fxe5 16. Bg5 Qe8 17. Qxe5 d6 18. Qxe8 Rxe8 19. Bxc8 ({Also possible is} 19. Bg2 Bg4) 19... Rexc8 20. Kg2 $14 {The knight on b6 is passive and White has the better structure. White may follow up with Ne1-d3.}) 11. Nf3 Ba6 {Other moves for Black are:} (11... Qg6 $5 12. Nd4 h5 $1 {Preventing h4-h5.} (12... c5 13. h5 Qb6 14. Nf3 $14) 13. Bg2 {[%cal Gg2e4] Threatening Be4.} (13. a3 Ba6 14. Qf3 Nxc2+ 15. Nxc2 Bxf1 16. Kxf1 Qxc2 17. Kg2 Be7 18. Rd1 Qg6 $11) 13... Ba6 14. Qe4 Bc5 {is better, and now White should play} ({Now taking the queen leads to a very good endgame for White:} 14... Qxe4+ 15. Bxe4 Bc5 16. Be3 Nd5 (16... O-O $2 17. Nxc6 $16) 17. Bxd5 cxd5 18. O-O-O $14 {White can follow up with Nf5 to eliminate Black's bishop pair and attack his weak pawns.}) 15. Nf5 $1 Nd5 (15... Qg4 $5 16. a3 {can be met with the amazing} Bd3 $13 {, leading to very unclear play.}) (15... Kf8 $5 {is also interesting:} 16. Be3 Bxe3 17. Nxe3 Qxe4 18. Bxe4 Re8 19. O-O-O ({Also possible are} 19. a3 Nd5 20. Bxd5 cxd5 21. O-O-O Bb7 $11) ({and} 19. f4 d6 20. Rd1 dxe5 21. f5 $44) 19... Rxe5 20. Bg2 Nxa2+ 21. Kb1 Nb4 22. Rxd7 Rh6 23. Rhd1 Rf6 $11) 16. Bd2 O-O 17. c4 {The following lines are very concrete:} Rae8 (17... Nb6 18. b4 $1 axb4 19. Be3 {Black cannot take the bishop because of 20. Ne7+. But again Black has a strong resource:} Rfe8 $1 20. Bxc5 d5 21. cxd5 cxd5 22. Qf4 Bd3 23. Bxb6 cxb6 24. Bxd5 (24. Ne3 b3 $13) 24... Ra5 25. Ne3 Rxd5 26. Nxd5 Qd6 $1 27. Ne3 (27. f3 Qxd5 28. Kf2 Qc5+ 29. Kg2 Qc2+ 30. Kg1 (30. Kh3 $2 Bf5+) 30... Qc5+ {Forcing a perpetual.}) 27... Qc5 28. Rd1 Qc3+ 29. Rd2 Qa1+ $11 {With another perpetual.}) (17... Rfe8 18. cxd5 cxd5 19. Qf4 Rab8 20. Bc3 d4 21. Nxd4 Rxb2 22. Be4 Qb6 23. Bd5 Re6 24. Rc1 Bb4 25. Qe3 $13) 18. cxd5 cxd5 19. Qf4 d6 ({After} 19... Bd3 {, White has the amazing move} 20. g4 {, opening access to Black's king.} hxg4 21. Ne3 d4 22. h5 Qb6 23. Nxg4 f5 24. Bd5+ Kh7 25. Qg3 Qb5 $8 26. Nf6+ $1 Rxf6 27. Qg6+ $1 Rxg6 28. hxg6+ Kxg6 29. Rg1+ $11 {, with a perpetual.}) 20. O-O-O Bd3 (20... dxe5 21. Qg5 $6 $14) (20... Rxe5 21. Nd4 $14) 21. g4 $1 hxg4 22. Ne3 dxe5 23. Qg5 (23. Qxg4 $6 Bxe3) ({and} 23. Qa4 d4 {are both at least satisfactory for Black.}) 23... c6 $44 (23... e4 24. Bf1 $14) 24. Bf1 (24. Rhg1 $5) 24... Be4 25. Rg1 Qxg5 26. hxg5 Rb8 {Black has good compensation for the piece.} 27. Bxa5 {now leads to a forced draw after} ({White can also play on with} 27. Rxg4 Bf3 28. Ra4 Bxd1 29. Nxd1 $13) 27... Ra8 28. b4 Rxa5 29. bxa5 Ba3+ 30. Kd2 Bb4+ $11) (11... Nxa2 {is dangerous for Black:} 12. Bf4 $1 (12. Bh3 $6 Qd5 {does not achieve much.}) 12... Bb4+ {is somewhat safer:} ({Now} 12... Nb4 $6 {looks risky:} 13. Ng5 $1 (13. Bh3 Qd5 $13) 13... Qf5 (13... Qg6 14. Ne4 h5 15. Bg2 $36) (13... Qe7 14. Bh3 $36) 14. Ne4 {, and the next moves are rather forced:} Nd5 15. Qf3 Nxf4 16. gxf4 Qe6 17. Bh3 Qc4 18. b3 Bb4+ 19. c3 Qxb3 20. O-O Be7 21. Rfb1 Qc4 22. f5 $40 {White has a dangerous attack.}) 13. Nd2 O-O {Now White has a choice.} 14. Qc4 $5 {looks most challenging:} (14. c3 {, and now Black should sacrifice the piece:} Nxc3 15. bxc3 Bxc3 16. Rc1 Qd5 $44 {, with reasonable compensation.}) ({White can also cut of the knight's protection with} 14. c4 d6 15. exd6 (15. Rxa2 dxe5 16. Be3 Qg6 $13) 15... Qg6 16. Bg2 Bg4 17. h5 Rae8 18. hxg6 Rxe2+ 19. Kf1 Bxd2 20. Rh4 Bxf4 21. gxh7+ Kh8 22. Rxg4 Rxb2 23. Rxf4 cxd6 24. Bxc6 $11 {, and this computer line ends with a drawish endgame.}) 14... Bxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Nb4 16. Qxe6 fxe6 17. Bg2 Nd5 18. Be3 d6 19. Ra3 $44 {Black's multiple weaknesses should easily outweigh his extra pawn.}) 12. c4 Qg6 ({After} 12... Bxc4 $2 13. Qxc4 Qxc4 14. Bxc4 Nc2+ 15. Kd1 Nxa1 16. Be3 $16 {, White will win the knight, with a clear advantage.}) (12... d5 $5 {leads to interesting play after} 13. Nd4 $1 {, with another branching point:} ({Here} 13. Bh3 $2 {is a mistake:} Qg6 14. h5 Qe4 $17) 13... Qe7 (13... Qg6 14. h5 Qe4 15. Qxe4 dxe4 16. Bd2 O-O-O (16... Bc5 17. a3 $14) (16... Be7 17. O-O-O $14) 17. a3 Nd3+ 18. Bxd3 exd3 19. Rh4 (19. Nxc6 Re8 $11) 19... Re8 20. O-O-O (20. Nf3 f6 $11) 20... Bxc4 21. Nxc6 Bd5 22. Nxa5 Rxe5 23. Bc3 Rf5 24. Rxd3 Be7 25. Rh2 Re8 $44 {Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 14. a3 $5 (14. Bg5 {leads to a forced draw after} Qc5 15. Rd1 dxc4 16. Qe4 Qd5 17. Bg2 Nd3+ 18. Kf1 Qxe4 19. Bxe4 Bb7 20. Kg2 Bc5 21. Nf5 g6 22. Bxd3 cxd3 23. Ng7+ Kf8 24. Bh6 Ke7 25. Bg5+ $11) (14. Nf5 $2 {fails due to} Bxc4 $17) 14... Bxc4 15. Qe3 c5 $1 (15... Bxf1 $2 {offers White a large advantage after} 16. Kxf1 Na6 17. Kg2 $16 {, and} c5 {can be answered with} 18. Qc3 $1) 16. Bxc4 (16. axb4 $2 cxd4) 16... cxd4 (16... dxc4 $5 17. axb4 cxd4 18. Qe4 (18. Qxd4 Rd8 {, followed by axb4, can only be better for Black.}) 18... Rb8 19. bxa5 Qe6 20. a6 Bb4+ 21. Ke2 O-O 22. a7 d3+ 23. Kf3 Ra8 24. Bf4 {, and Black can equalise after} Bc5 $11) 17. Qf3 c6 ({Or} 17... Qc5 18. Bb3 $44) 18. Bb3 $5 (18. O-O dxc4 19. axb4 Qe6 20. bxa5 Qd5 (20... Bc5 $5) 21. Qd1 Bb4 22. Bd2 Bxd2 23. Qxd2 O-O 24. Rfc1 Rfd8 $11 {The two strong passers will neutralise each other.}) 18... Na6 19. O-O Nc5 20. Bc2 $44 {Offers White good compensation due to his better development and his bishop pair.}) (12... h5 {Here White has a choice:} 13. a3 (13. Ng5 Qg6 14. Ne4 ({Or} 14. Kd1 O-O-O $13) 14... f5 15. Ng5 f4 $13 {is highly unclear.}) 13... Bxc4 14. Qxc4 Qxc4 15. Bxc4 Nc2+ 16. Ke2 Nxa1 17. Bd2 Nc2 18. Bd3 {Now Black can give up the trapped bishop for two pawns, resulting in an approximately equal endgame.} Nxa3 19. bxa3 Bxa3 20. Ra1 Bc5 $11) 13. h5 (13. Kd1 {is rather risky:} c5 14. a3 Nc6 15. h5 ({Or} 15. Bd2 Be7) 15... Qe6 $132 {Black will castle long and the king on d1 doesn't feel very safe.}) 13... Qc2 14. Rh4 Qxe2+ (14... Be7 15. Bg5 (15. Rg4 c5 16. a3 Qxe2+ 17. Kxe2 Nc6 18. Kd1 g6 $11) 15... Bxg5 {This is Black's safest option.} ({Also playable but somewhat risky is} 15... f6 $5 16. exf6 gxf6 17. Bh6 O-O-O 18. Rd1 d5 $13) 16. Nxg5 {, and now} h6 (16... Rb8 $2 {1/2-1/2 (43) Cheparinov,I (2667)-Svane,R (2615) Krasnaya Polyana 2021} 17. Qd2 $1 $18) 17. Nf3 {transposes to the main line.}) (14... Bc5 15. Be3 Qxe2+ (15... Bxe3 16. fxe3 {is similar.}) 16. Kxe2 Bxe3 17. fxe3 c5 18. Bh3 Rb8 19. b3 Bb7 $11 {White's position looks slightly more pleasant but objectively the endgame should be equal.}) 15. Kxe2 Be7 16. Bg5 Bxg5 17. Nxg5 h6 18. Nf3 c5 19. Bh3 ({Or} 19. Bg2 Bb7 20. a3 Nc6 21. Rd1 Rb8 $11) 19... Rd8 20. a3 (20. Rd1 Ke7) 20... Nc6 21. Rd1 $11 {White can try to exert some more pressure, but with correct play Black should hold.} *

